me of the Year\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | last = Khan | first = Zarmena | url = http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2016/03/20/sxsw-gaming-awards-2016-winners/ | title = The Witcher 3 and Bloodborne Shine in SXSW 2016 Gaming Awards | publisher = PlayStation LifeStyle | date = March 20, 2016 | accessdate = February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Excellence in Technical Achievement\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Excellence in Design\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"20\" |15th [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] (NAVGTR) awards\n| Game of the Year\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"20\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web | url = http://navgtr.org/winners/2015-winners/ | title = 2015 Winners | publisher = [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] | date = March 21, 2016 | accessdate = February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Animation, Artistic\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Art Direction, Period Influence\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Art Direction, Contemporary\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Camera Direction in a Game Engine\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Character Design\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Costume Design\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Direction in a Game Cinema\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Game Design, Franchise\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Game Engineering\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Graphics, Technical\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Performance in a Drama, Lead\n| Brian T. Delaney as \"Male Player Character\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Performance in a Drama, Supporting\n| Stephen Russell as \"Codsworth/Nick Valentine\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Song, Original or Adapted\n| \"Good Neighbor\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Song Collection\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Sound Editing in a Game Cinema\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Sound Effects\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Use of Sound, Franchise\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Writing in a Drama\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Game, Franchise Role Playing\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[12th British Academy Games Awards|12th]] [[British Academy Games Awards]]\n| [[British Academy Games Award for Best Game|Best Game]]\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | last = Skrebels | first = Joe | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/03/10/bafta-games-awards-2016-nominees-revealed | title = BAFTA Games Awards 2016 Nominees Revealed | publisher = [[IGN]] | date = March 10, 2016 | accessdate = March 11, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Music\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| [[Game Critics Awards]] 2017\n| Best VR Game\n| ''Fallout 4 VR''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/nominees.html | title = Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2017 (2017 Nominees) | publisher = [[Game Critics Awards]] | accessdate = February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Gamescom]] 2017\n| Best Virtual Reality Game\n| ''Fallout 4 VR''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news | url = http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/24/super-mario-odyssey-sweeps-best-of-gamescom-awards-6876988/ | title = Super Mario Odyssey sweeps Best Of Gamescom awards | newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] | publisher = [[DMG Media]] | date = August 24, 2017 | accessdate = February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"3\" |17th [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] (NAVGTR) awards\n| Control Design, VR\n| ''Fallout 4 VR''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | url = http://navgtr.org/archives/3351/ | title = Nominee List for 2017 | publisher = [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] | date = February 9, 2018 | accessdate = February 15, 2018 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20180215172210/http://navgtr.org/archives/3351/ | archive-date = February 15, 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://navgtr.org/archives/3365/ | title = Horizon wins 7; Mario GOTY | publisher = [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] | date = March 13, 2018 | accessdate = March 14, 2018 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20180314070824/http://navgtr.org/archives/3365/ | archive-date = March 14, 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| Direction in Virtual Reality\n| ''Fallout 4 VR''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Sound Mixing in Virtual Reality\n| ''Fallout 4 VR''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|4741306}}\n{{Portal bar|United States|Nuclear technology|Speculative fiction|Video games}}\n{{Fallout}}\n{{DICE GOTY}}\n{{BAFTA Games BG}}\n\n[[Category:2015 video games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:AIAS Game of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) video games]]\n[[Category:Bethesda Game Studios games]]\n[[Category:Cannibalism in fiction]]\n[[Category:Cryonics in fiction]]\n[[Category:Fallout video games]]\n[[Category:HTC Vive games]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 Pro enhanced games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Valve Index games]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games about robots]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring protagonists of selectable gender]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Inon Zur]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 23rd century]]\n[[Category:Video games with alternate endings]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One X enhanced games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = Fallout 4\n| image      = Fallout 4 cover art.jpg\n| developer  = [[Bethesda Game Studios]]{{efn|Additional work by [[id Software]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Tamoor|last=Hussain|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4-gun-gameplay-built-with-doom-devs-help/1100-6430602/|title=Fallout 4 Gun Gameplay Built With Doom Dev's Help|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=September 16, 2015|accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| publisher  = [[Bethesda Softworks]]\n| director   = [[Todd Howard]]\n| producer   = {{Unbulleted list|Ashley Cheng|Jeff Gardiner}}\n| designer   = [[Emil Pagliarulo]]\n| programmer = Guy Carver\n| artist     = [[Istvan Pely]]\n| writer     = Emil Pagliarulo\n| composer   = [[Inon Zur]]\n| series     = ''[[Fallout (series)|Fallout]]''\n| engine     = [[Creation Engine]]\n| platforms  = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released   = November 10, 2015\n| genre      = [[Action role-playing]]\n| modes      = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Fallout 4''''' is an [[action role-playing game]] developed by [[Bethesda Game Studios]] and published by [[Bethesda Softworks]]. It is the fourth main game in the [[Fallout (series)|''Fallout'' series]] and was released worldwide on November 10, 2015, for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]]. The game is set within an [[open world]] [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] environment that encompasses the city of [[Boston]] and the surrounding [[Massachusetts]] region known as \"The Commonwealth\". The main story takes place in the year 2287, ten years after the events of ''[[Fallout 3]]'' and 210 years after \"The Great War\", which caused [[Nuclear holocaust|catastrophic nuclear devastation]] across the United States.\n\nThe player assumes control of a character referred to as the \"Sole Survivor\", who emerges from a long-term cryogenic stasis in Vault 111, an underground nuclear [[fallout shelter]]. After witnessing the murder of their spouse and kidnapping of their son, the Sole Survivor ventures out into the Commonwealth to search for their missing child. The player explores the game's dilapidated world, completes various quests, helps out factions, and acquires experience points to level up and increase the abilities of their character. New features to the series include the ability to develop and manage settlements and an extensive crafting system where materials scavenged from the environment can be used to craft drugs and explosives, upgrade weapons and armor, and construct, furnish and improve settlements. ''Fallout 4'' also marks the first game in the series to feature full voice acting for the protagonist.\n\n''Fallout 4'' received positive reviews from critics with many praising the world depth, player freedom, overall amount of content, crafting, and soundtrack, while criticism was mainly directed at the game's visuals and technical issues. The game was a commercial and critical success, generating {{US$|750 million|long=no}} within the first 24 hours of its launch, and received numerous accolades from various gaming publications and award events, including the respective awards for Game of the Year and Best Game at the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]] and [[British Academy Games Awards]]. Bethesda has released [[Fallout 4 downloadable content|six downloadable content]] add-ons, including the expansions ''[[Fallout 4: Far Harbor|Far Harbor]]'' and ''[[Fallout 4: Nuka-World|Nuka-World]]''.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Fallout 4'' is an [[action role-playing game]] set in an [[open world]] environment. Gameplay is similar to that of ''[[Fallout 3]]'' and ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]'', the two previous primary iterations in the series. Returning features include a camera that can switch between a [[First person (video games)|first-person]] and [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]]. ''Fallout 4'' introduces features including a layered armor system, base-building, a dialogue system featuring 111,000 lines of dialogue,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2015/09/05/bethesda-completes-recording-of-fallout-4-39-s-111-000-lines-of-dialogue.aspx|title=Bethesda Completes Recording Of Fallout 4's 111,000 Lines Of Dialogue|first=Kyle|last=Hilliard|date=September 5, 2015|accessdate=October 19, 2015|work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref> and a crafting system which implements every lootable object in the game. Enemies such as Mole Rats, Raiders, Super Mutants, Deathclaws, and Feral Ghouls return, along with the companion [[Dogmeat (Fallout)|Dogmeat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/fallout-4s-dogmeat-cannot-be-killed/|title=Fallout 4's Dogmeat cannot be killed|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=June 17, 2015|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe player has the ability to freely roam in the game's world and leave a conversation at any time. If the player has discovered a certain location they may [[fast travel]] to it. Weapons can be customized too; the game includes over 50 guns, which can be crafted with a variety of modifications, such as barrel types and laser focus, with over 700 modifications available. Power Armor has been redesigned to be more like a vehicle than an equipable suit of armor, requiring energy cores and being essentially dead weight without it<ref name=\"Fo4 Trailer\">{{cite AV media |people=Bethesda Softworks |date=June 15, 2015 |title=Fallout 4 \u2013 E3 Showcase World Premiere |medium=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GE2BkLqMef4 |access-date=June 28, 2015 |publisher=[[Bethesda Softworks]]}}</ref> and can be modified, allowing the player to add items such as a jetpack or selecting separate types of armor for each part of the suit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/fallout-4-screenshots-and-art-show-customisation-mutants-more/|title=Fallout 4 screenshots show jetpacks, mutants, more|last=Sykes|first=Tom|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref>\n\nA new feature to the series is the ability to craft and deconstruct settlements and buildings. The player can select and break down many in-game objects and structures, and use them to freely build their own structures. In addition, the towns can be powered with working electricity, using a power line system. Merchants and [[non-player character]]s can inhabit the player's settlements, for which the player must provide sustenance by growing food in makeshift patches and building water pumps. The player can build various defenses around their settlements, such as turrets and traps, to defend against random attacks.<ref name=\"crafting\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/fallout-4s-crafting-system-is-bonkers-1711322298|title=Fallout 4's Crafting System Looks Awesome|last=Hernandez|first=Patricia|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015|work=[[Kotaku]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Fallout 4 V.A.T.S. Screen.jpg|thumb|left|When using V.A.T.S., real-time action is slowed down, and players can see the probability of hitting each body part of the enemies through a percentage ratio displayed here on the PlayStation 4 version.]]\n\nThe Pip-Boy, a personal computing device strapped to the player character's wrist, allows the player to access a menu with statistics, maps, data, and items the player has acquired. The player can find game cartridges, which can be played on the Pip-Boy or a terminal. A new feature for the Pip-Boy interface is a downloadable application for iOS, Android, and Windows smartphones and tablets. This optional app allows players to access the Pip-Boy interface on a separate screen, and play the collected game cartridges when not playing the main game. Another returning gameplay feature is the Vault-Tec Assisted Targeting System (V.A.T.S.). While using V.A.T.S., real-time combat is slowed down (instead of stopped entirely as in previous entries), and action is played out from varying camera angles in a computer graphics version of \"[[bullet time]]\". Various actions cost points, limiting the actions of each combatant during a period of time, and the player can target specific body parts for attacks to inflict specific injuries; headshots can be used for quick kills or to blind, legs can be targeted to slow enemy movement, and opponents can be disarmed by shooting at their weapons. Unlike previous games, in which the player had a random chance to inflict a critical hit, they are now performed manually through V.A.T.S.<ref name=\"First Gameplay\">{{cite web|url=http://ign.com/articles/2015/06/15/e3-2015-fallout-4s-first-gameplay-and-story-details|title=E3 2015: Fallout 4's First Gameplay Details|last=Ingenito|first=Vince|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=June 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the game, players are given points to spend on a character progression system called [[Fallout (video game)#SPECIAL system|S.P.E.C.I.A.L.]]. The system represents seven statistics, namely strength, perception, endurance, charisma, intelligence, agility, and luck. When the player earns enough [[experience point]]s to gain a new level, they unlock an ability. When the player allocates more points to a statistic, more abilities can be unlocked. These perks can be upgraded to improve the protagonist's efficiency and to further unlock abilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/7/24/9036527/fallout-4-romance-options-upgrades-special-customization-progression|title=How Fallout 4 handles romance, character progression and more|first=Griffin|last=McElroy|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 25, 2015|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> There are about 275 perks available for the player to unlock. There is no level cap and the game does not end once the main story is complete.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pcgamer.com/fallout-4-will-have-no-level-cap-and-no-hard-finish/ | title=Fallout 4 will have no level cap and no hard finish | work=[[PC Gamer]] | publisher=[[Future Publishing]] | first=Andy | last=Chalk | date=August 6, 2015 | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe player may travel with only one companion at a time, although other characters also accompany the player in certain quests. For the first time in the series, these companions can interact with the environment on the player character's behalf. For example, if the player character does not have required skills to hack a terminal or pick a lock, they can order the companion to do it for them. Any companion present besides Dogmeat will react to certain player actions in one of four ways (love, like, dislike, or hate), which either raises or lowers their \"affinity\". Raising a companion's affinity to 1,000 points will result in them \"idolizing\" the player and granting a specific perk. The companion will leave if affinity drops low enough, and some actions can turn them hostile on sight. {{Clear}}\n\n== Plot ==\n\n=== Setting ===\n''Fallout 4'' takes place in the year 2287, ten years after the events of ''[[Fallout 3]]'' and 210 years after the Great War, a war between the United States and China over natural resources that ended in a [[nuclear holocaust]] in 2077. The setting is a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[Retrofuturism|retro-future]], covering a region that includes [[Boston]] and other parts of [[New England]] known as \"The Commonwealth\". Unlike the previous titles, ''Fallout 4''{{'}}s story begins on the day the bombs dropped: October 23, 2077.\n\nThe game takes place in an alternate version of history that sees the 1940s and 1950s aesthetics such as diners and a drive-in theater. The design and technology advance in the directions imagined at the time. The resulting universe is thus a [[Retrofuturism|retro-futuristic]] one, where the technology has evolved enough to produce [[Directed-energy weapon|laser weapons]], [[Genetic engineering|manipulate genes]] and create nearly-autonomous [[artificial intelligence]], but all within the confines of 1950s solutions such as the widespread use of atomic power and [[vacuum tube]]s, as well as having the integrated circuitry of the digital age. The architecture, advertisements and general living styles are also depicted to be largely unchanged since the 1950s, while including contemporary products, such as a robotic rocking horse for children in one advertisement, or posters for the underground Vaults that play a central role in the storyline of the game.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThere are four main factions that the player can choose to support throughout the story; the Brotherhood of Steel, an anti-[[Android (robot)|synth]] faction hoping to preserve technology in the Commonwealth; the Institute, a secretive organization that specializes in the creation of synths; the Minutemen; a faction that aims to drive out raiders and other threats to the Commonwealth; and the Railroad, a secretive organization dedicated to rescuing synths from the Institute.\n\n=== Characters ===\nThe player's character (voiced by either [[Brian T. Delaney]] or [[Courtenay Taylor]]) takes shelter in Vault 111, emerging exactly 210 years later on October 23, 2287, and assuming the name of the \"Sole Survivor\".<ref name=\"guardiane3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jun/15/fallout-4-release-date-and-details-plus-dishonored-2|title=Fallout 4: release date and details, plus Dishonored 2|last=Stuart|first=Keith|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> There are thirteen possible companions in the story. [[Dogmeat (Fallout)|Dogmeat]], a loyal [[German Shepherd]], is the only mandatory companion, but six others must at least be encountered; Codsworth ([[Stephen Russell]]), the Sole Survivor's robot butler; Deacon (Ryan Alosio), a Railroad agent; John Hancock (Danny Shorago), the mayor of Goodneighbor; Nick Valentine (Stephen Russell), a synth detective; Piper Wright ([[Courtney Ford]]), an intrepid reporter; and Preston Garvey (Jon Gentry), the reluctant leader of the Minutemen. The other six possible companions are Cait (Katy Townsend), an Irish-accented cage fighter; Curie ([[Sophie Simone Cortina]]), a robot scientist turned Synth; Danse ([[Peter Jessop]]), a Brotherhood of Steel Paladin; MacCready ([[Matthew Mercer]]), a mercenary; Strong ([[Sean Schemmel]]), a human-sympathetic Super Mutant; and X6-88 (David Paluck), an Institute Courser. Seven companions become romance options once they idolize the Sole Survivor: Cait, Curie, Danse, Hancock, MacCready, Piper, and Preston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/fallout-4-has-12-companions-you-can-romance-all-the-human-ones-296611.phtml|title=Fallout 4 has 12 companions, you can romance all the human ones|first=Steven|last=Hansen|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Story ===\nThe story begins in 2077 in Sanctuary Hills, located near [[Concord, Massachusetts]]. The player character is at home with their spouse (Nate or Nora depending on the player character's gender), their son Shaun, and Codsworth. A Vault-Tec representative admits the family into Vault 111, the local [[fallout shelter]]. Moments later, a news bulletin warns of an incoming nuclear attack. As the detonation occurs, the family evacuates to the Vault, where they are tricked into entering [[Cryogenics|cryogenic]] tubes and [[cryonics|frozen alive]]. After an unknown number of years, they are reawakened by two strangers, who murder the player's spouse and kidnap Shaun. The player is put back into cryogenic sleep and awakens again when the life support system malfunctions. The player, nicknamed the \"Sole Survivor\" of Vault 111, vows to avenge their spouse's death and find Shaun.\n\nThe Sole Survivor heads home to find Sanctuary Hills in ruins. They reunite with Codsworth, revealing that 210 years have passed since the war. Codsworth suggests that the Survivor goes to Concord for help. The Survivor finds and befriends Dogmeat, and assists the Minutemen faction in evacuating to Sanctuary Hills. The Sole Survivor travels to Diamond City, a fortified settlement based in the ruins of [[Fenway Park]], where they meet Piper. There, they learn about a secretive organization called the Institute that has been terrifying the Commonwealth by kidnapping people and replacing them with \"synths\", synthetic humans indistinguishable from real humans.\n\nWith the help of Nick Valentine, the Sole Survivor uncovers the identity of their spouse's killer: Conrad Kellogg ([[Keythe Farley]]). After learning from Kellogg that Shaun is being held in the Institute, the Sole Survivor kills him and retrieves a cybernetic implant from his brain to access his memories. During this time, the Brotherhood of Steel arrives in the Commonwealth on the ''Prydwen'', an [[airship]]. The Sole Survivor learns from Brian Virgil (Matthew Waterson), an ex-Institute scientist, that teleportation is the only way to enter the Institute. After the Survivor retrieves a chip and decodes it with the help of the Railroad, Virgil provides the blueprints for a teleportation device, which the Sole Survivor constructs by allying with the Brotherhood, Minutemen, or Railroad.\n\nThe Sole Survivor successfully enters the Institute and discovers that Shaun is the Institute's director. Shaun, now an old man calling himself Father ([[Tony Amendola]]), reveals that he was kidnapped by Kellogg to become a specimen for synth experiments due to his pure pre-war DNA, and that the Sole Survivor remained in stasis for a further sixty years before being reawakened. He invites the Sole Survivor to join the Institute. If accepted, Shaun reveals that he is dying of cancer and wishes for the Survivor to become his successor. After initiating a purge in the Commonwealth, wiping out the Brotherhood and Railroad, the Survivor assumes control of the Institute after Shaun's death. Otherwise, the Sole Survivor devises a plan with their faction to fight the Institute. Siding with the Brotherhood or Railroad will force the Sole Survivor to destroy the other faction. The Sole Survivor detonates a nuclear reactor, destroying the Institute. After this feat, if the Survivor sided with the Minutemen, they must lastly wipe out any remaining hostile faction. Otherwise, they will remain neutral.\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:ToddHoward2010sm.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Todd Howard (video game designer)|Todd Howard]], game director of both ''Fallout 4'' and ''[[Fallout 3]]'', in 2010]]\n\nThe initial plans for ''Fallout 4'' were formed in 2009, when director Todd Howard wanted to explore the world of ''Fallout'' before the bombs fell. Thus, a team began production on the game that year, including [[Istvan Pely]], lead artist of ''[[Fallout 3]]'', after finishing that game's [[downloadable content]] (DLC). Meanwhile, development on ''[[The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim]]'' had Bethesda's full attention, and after that game released in 2011, the studio continued to regularly support it until 2013 with updates and DLC. After that content was finished, ''Fallout 4'' entered full production from mid-2013 to mid-2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/inside-the-fallout-4-development-team-2015-12|title=Inside the Fallout 4 development team|website=[[Business Insider]]|author=Ben Gilbert|date=December 3, 2015|accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\n\nUnlike the previous two titles\u2014''Fallout 3'' and ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]''\u2014which used the [[Gamebryo]] [[Game engine|engine]], ''Fallout 4'' uses the [[Creation Engine]], which was used in ''[[The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim]]''. Modified for ''Fallout 4'', the Creation Engine includes a revamped character editor system that allows freeform creation of faces without the use of sliders seen in previous games. Instead, the player can click and drag each feature of the face to accurately customize their character, which can either be a man or woman as the previous ''Fallout'' titles have featured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/fallout-4-kind-still-running-oblivion-engine-do-not-fear-bethesda-face/|title=Fallout 4 kind of still uses the Oblivion engine, but do not fear 'Bethesda face'|last=Houghton|first=David|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015|work=[[GamesRadar]]}}</ref> Bethesda announced that the game would run at 1080p resolution and 30 [[frames per second]] on PlayStation 4 and Xbox One.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4-will-run-1080p-30fps-on-ps4-xbox-one-pc-/1100-6428362/|title=Fallout 4 Will Run 1080p/30fps on PS4, Xbox One, \"PC Not Limited in Any Way\"|work=[[GameSpot]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|first=Tamoor|last=Hussain|date=June 22, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Bethesda revealed that mobile devices would be integrated into the game as a form of [[second screen]], acting as a secondary display for the Pip-Boy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/11/11/9714010/heres-my-fallout-4-pip-boy-and-it-only-cost-10-dollars|title=Here's my Fallout 4 Pip-Boy, and it only cost $10|last=Hall|first=Charlie|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=November 28, 2015|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the first time in the ''Fallout'' series, the player's character, the Sole Survivor, is fully voice acted, including all decision-based dialogue options.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2015/06/14/fallout-4-gives-voice-to-vault-survivor.aspx|title=Fallout 4 Gives Voice To Vault Survivor|last=Kato|first=Matthew|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015|work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref> [[Brian T. Delaney]] and Courtenay Taylor are the two player character voice actors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/06/23/meet-the-voices-of-fallout-4s-not-silent-protagonists/|title=Meet the voices of Fallout 4\u2032s not-silent protagonists|work=[[VG247]]|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref>{{Repetition inline|date=December 2017}}\n\nTodd Howard revealed that [[Mod (video gaming)|mods]] for the PC versions of the game would be usable on the Xbox One version and that the team hoped to bring them to the PlayStation 4 version eventually.<ref name=\"xbox1mods\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/06/15/fallout-4-pc-mods-work-on-xbox-one/|title=Your 'Fallout 4' PC mods will work fine on the Xbox One, too|last=Velazco|first=Chris|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015|work=[[Engadget]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/584490/Fallout-4-Bethesda-E3-Xbox-One-PS4-Fallout-Shelter-Apple|title= Bethesda E3 announce 2015 release date and modding for Xbox One and PS4|last=Jones|first=Gary|work=[[Express.co.uk]]|date=June 15, 2015|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> When asked about the failed effort to add a paid mod system to ''[[The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim]]'', Howard stated there were no plans for a similar effort with ''Fallout 4''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/video-games/conferences/e3-2015/14176-Fallout-4-Won-t-Have-Paid-Mods|title=No Plans For Fallout 4 Paid Mods, Says Bethesda|last=Bogos|first=Steven|date=June 19, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]}}</ref> The mods created by PC players through The Creation Kit, which contains the official modding tools, were released for Xbox One and PlayStation 4 in May 2016 and November 2016 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-27-fallout-4-mods-come-to-xbox-one-in-may-ps4-in-june|title=Fallout 4 mods come to Xbox One in May, PS4 in June|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/9/12862030/playstation-4-mods-skyrim-fallout-canceled|title=Fallout 4 and Skyrim are no longer getting mods on PS4|publisher=|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/10/5/13177296/fallout-4-ps4-mods-confirmed-skyrim-special-edition-ps4-pro-4k-support|title=Fallout 4 and Skyrim Special Edition will get mod support on PS4 after all|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|date=October 5, 2016|website=Polygon|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/de/devnote/1XOpTkf8QA8iYAaCG8mAog/fallout-4-1-8-update|title=Bethesda.net|website=Bethesda.net|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Engine ===\n{{Main|Creation Engine}}\n\n''Fallout 4'' uses Bethesda's Creation Engine, which was created for ''The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Skyrim Performance Review: It's Definitely a DirectX 9 Game|url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/244400/skyrim_performance_review_its_definitely_a_directx_9_game.html|website = PCWorld|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> Just after ''Fallout 3''{{'}}s release, the team devised numerous design objectives to meet for ''Skyrim''\u2014which were updated for ''Fallout 4''{{'}}s hardware requirements. The updated Creation Engine allows for graphical improvements over Bethesda's previous efforts. For instance, the draw distance renders much farther than in previous ''Fallout'' games.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nDynamic lighting allows shadows to be created by any structure or item in the game world. Howard stated in the E3 Press Conference{{When|date=December 2017}} that the updated Creation Engine allows for next-generation [[god ray]]s and advanced volumetric lighting.{{vague|date=May 2017}} The engine features a variety of visual effects not present in previous Bethesda games such as motion blur, temporal anti-aliasing, height fog, dynamic dismemberment, screen space reflections, filmic tone mapping, an updated material system\u2014for wet textures\u2014among numerous others.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bethesda Shows Off ''Fallout 4'' Graphics \u2013 NVIDIA Volumetric Lighting Used \u2013 Legit Reviews|url = http://www.legitreviews.com/bethesda-shows-off-fallout-4-graphics-nvidia-volumetric-lighting-used_174993|website = Legit Reviews|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> The engine allows the Bethesda team to add more dynamic lighting to every scene as well as \"paint surfaces with realistic materials\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fallout 4: how Creation Engine enhancements make the game shine|url = https://www.vg247.com/2015/11/04/fallout-4-pc-ps4-xbox-one-creation-engine/|website = VG247.com|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> Bethesda released an example on how the engine works: \"When a rain storm rolls in, our new material system allows the surfaces of the world to get wet, and a new cloth simulation system makes cloth, hair, and vegetation blow in the wind.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bethesda.net|url = https://bethesda.net/en/article/2Y37xeRPeUW0EgkgaKW8oA/the-graphics-technology-of-fallout-4|website = Bethesda.net|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe updated Creation Engine allows for a more advanced character creation system, which uses sculpting\u2014forgoing the series of sliders present in previous games. In detail, the new character creation system introduces a new, freeform, slider-free facial editor controlled via dynamic, real-time modeling interface.<ref>{{Cite web|title = ''Fallout 4'' kind of still uses the ''Oblivion'' engine, but do not fear 'Bethesda face'|url = http://www.gamesradar.com/fallout-4-kind-still-running-oblivion-engine-do-not-fear-bethesda-face/|website = GamesRadar+|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith regards to the aforementioned fluid animations, the updated engine also allows a much more open approach to conversations with NPCs\u2014wherein the camera views can change depending on the player's preference from a first-person view to a cinematic third-person view\u2014compared to ''Fallout 3''{{'}}s rigid and instanced conversation system. The protagonist features dynamic dialogue, which is context sensitive and allows players to back out of a conversation. In Howard's words, \"you are free to walk away anytime if you want, or you can even shoot him in the face.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fallout 4 Features Dynamic Dialog And Dog Commands \u00ab  GamingBolt.com: Video Game News, Reviews, Previews and Blog|url = http://gamingbolt.com/fallout-4-features-dynamic-dialog-and-dog-commands|website = gamingbolt.com|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing and release ==\n[[File:Fallout4Car.jpg|thumb|left|A custom [[Volkswagen Type 2]] promoting ''Fallout 4'' at [[gamescom 2015]]]]\n\nOn June 2, 2015, Bethesda published a countdown timer scheduled to expire on June 3, 2015, at 14:00 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/02/fallout-4-countdown-clock-appears-runs-out-tomorrow|title=Fallout 4 Countdown Clock Appears, Runs Out Tomorrow|last=Karmali|first=Luke|work=IGN|date=June 2, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> The game's website went live slightly ahead of schedule, revealing the game along with its box art and platforms.<ref name=\"GameSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4-officially-confirmed-for-pc-xbox-one-ps4/1100-6427776/|title=Fallout 4 Officially Confirmed for PC, Xbox One, PS4|last=Hussain|first=Tamoor|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2015|work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/03/fallout-4-officially-revealed-by-teaser-site|title=Fallout 4 Officially Revealed With In-Game Trailer|last=Karmali|first=Luke|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2015|work=[[IGN]]}}</ref> The site was taken down later but was put back up again at the scheduled time. The trailer was released when the countdown timer expired,<ref name=\"Fo4 Trailer\"/> and the game was confirmed to take place in Boston and its surrounding Massachusetts countryside, as suggested by earlier rumors.<ref name=\"Kotaku1\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/all-the-juicy-details-hidden-in-the-fallout-4-trailer-1708720494|title=All The Juicy Details Hidden In The Fallout 4 Trailer|last=Hernandez|first=Patricia|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=June 4, 2015|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-32996003|title=Fallout 4 confirmed for release by Bethesda \u2013 BBC News|last=Lee|first=Dave|work=BBC News|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> More details were given during Bethesda's [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2015|E3 2015]] press conference on June 14, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/02/10/bethesda-hosting-its-first-ever-e3-conference-in-2015|title=Bethesda Hosting its First Ever E3 Conference in 2015|last=Karmali|first=Luke|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=February 10, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/fallout-4-announced-trailer-and-details-revealed-ahead-of-e3-launch-10294953.html|title=Fallout 4 announced: trailer and details revealed ahead of E3 launch|last=Griffin|first=Andrew|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=June 3, 2015|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\n\n''Fallout 4'' became available for pre-order following the product announcement. In addition to the standard edition of the game, there is a collector's edition which includes a wearable replica of the Pip-Boy. This is able to house a smartphone device, which can run the [[second screen]] functionality of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/6/18/8800037/fallout-4-pip-boy-wearable-e3-2015|title=Here's a first look at Fallout 4's Pip-Boy wearable|last=Miller|first=Ross|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref> As a [[pre-order]] bonus for the Windows version of the game, an announcer pack featuring the voice of Mister Handy was released for the [[multiplayer online battle arena]] game, ''[[Dota 2]]'', developed by [[Valve Corporation|Valve]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frank|first1=Allegra|title=Fallout 4 meets Dota 2 with Mister Handy announcer pack|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/10/22/9598500/fallout-4-dota-2-mister-handy-announcer-pack-steam|website=Polygon|accessdate=June 27, 2016}}</ref> Bethesda announced that ''Fallout 4'' had [[gone gold]] on October 23, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Fallout 4 Has Gone Gold \u2013 IGN|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/10/23/fallout-4-has-gone-gold|work=IGN|accessdate=November 2, 2015|last=Osborn|date=October 23, 2015|first=Alex}}</ref> The game was released for Windows, PlayStation 4 and Xbox One on November 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2015/6/14/8780151/fallout-4-release-date-bethesda-softworks|title=Fallout 4 will be out Nov. 10, 2015|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|date=June 14, 2015|website=Polygon|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Updates ===\nAfter ''Fallout 4''{{'}}s release, Bethesda has released several patches to address some of the issues that were present at the game's launch along with presenting features that improve general gameplay. The first patch\u2014coded as patch 1.2\u2014fine-tuned the game by improving the frame rate. Patch 1.2 fixed a few bugs and errors present at the launch of the game but interfered with unofficial mod support.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.extremetech.com/gaming/219226-new-fallout-4-1-2-patch-improves-performance-on-all-platforms-but-at-a-cost| title = New Fallout 4 1.2 patch improves performance on all platforms \u2014 but at a cost {{!}} ExtremeTech| website = ExtremeTech| access-date = March 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.techtimes.com/articles/115690/20151212/fallout-4-patch-1-2-reportedly-breaks-mod-support-here-s-how-to-fix-it.htm\n| title = \u2018Fallout 4\u2019 Patch 1.2 Reportedly Breaks Mod Support: Here\u2019s How To Fix It| date = December 12, 2015| website = Tech Times| access-date = March 1, 2016}}</ref> Patch 1.3 improved the game's graphics on all platforms, along with presenting the game with new features such as an added status menu for settlers in settlements. With regard to the graphical updates introduced in this patch, the PC platform was given a new weapon debris effect and a new ambient occlusion setting. The patch fixed several bugs and glitches present in the game.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.pcauthority.com.au/News/414503,fallout-4-pc-patch-13-out-now.aspx| title = Fallout 4 PC patch 1.3 out now| website = PC & Tech Authority| access-date = March 1, 2016}}</ref> Patch 1.4 was designed to ready the game for the upcoming Creation Kit and downloadable content. Patch 1.4 brought a variety of additions to the settlement building mechanic of the game by adding a symbol to new content placed in by the modding community along with adding a variety of items, such as Raider and Super Mutant decors. The patch also brought general improvements to the game's stability.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.dayherald.com/fallout-4-patch-1-4-brings-a-number-of-additions-fixes-and-performance-tweaks-to-the-game/10333/| title = Fallout 4: Patch 1.4 Brings A Number of Additions, Fixes and Performance Tweaks to The Game! {{!}} Day Herald| website = www.dayherald.com| access-date = March 1, 2016}}</ref> The 1.5 patch added a revamped survival mode along with support for the downloadable and included bug fixes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4s-new-update-arrives-on-ps4xbox-one-addin/1100-6439560/|title=Fallout 4's New Update Arrives on PS4/Xbox One, Adding Survival Mode|website=GameSpot|access-date=May 6, 2016}}</ref> Similar to the previous Bethesda games, ''Fallout 4''{{'}}s fan community-created [[unofficial patch]]es to address issues and bugs unaddressed by the official patches.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/fallout-4s-unofficial-patch-nukes-dozens-of-bugs/ |title=Fallout 4's unofficial patch nukes dozens of bugs |author=Christopher Livingston |date=24 April 2016 |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=2017-11-11 |language=en }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2016/04/fallout-4s-unofficial-patch-tries-to-fix-everything-bethesda-cant/ |title=Fallout 4's Unofficial Patch Tries To Fix Everything Bethesda Can't |author=Alex Walker |date=26 April 2016 |publisher=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=2017-11-11 |language=}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/fallout-4-unofficial-patch-runs-into-a-bug-even-it-cannot-fix/ |title=Fallout 4 Unofficial Patch runs into a bug even it cannot fix |first=Andy|last=Chalk|date=2016-07-11 |accessdate=2017-06-06 |magazine=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[E3 2016]], a [[virtual reality]] mode for the game was announced, to be released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/6/12/11917524/bethesda-e3-2016-fallout-4-htc-vive-virtual-reality|title=Virtual reality Fallout 4 is coming to HTC Vive in 2017|website=theverge|access-date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> ''Fallout 4 VR'' was released as a stand-alone game on December 4, 2017, for PC on the [[HTC Vive]] platform.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/08/23/fallout-4-vr-doom-vfr-and-skyrim-vr-release-dates-announced |title=Fallout 4 VR, Doom VFR, and Skyrim VR Release Dates Announced |last=Sirani |first=Jordan |date=August 23, 2017 |website=IGN.com |access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Downloadable content ===\n{{main|Fallout 4 downloadable content}}\nOn February 16, 2016, Bethesda announced details, prices, and release dates for the first three add-ons for ''Fallout 4''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/3U2q1EOhUcymEmeKEYes60/fallout-4-add-ons-automatron-wasteland-workshop-far-harbor-and-more|title=Fallout 4 Add-Ons \u2013 Automatron, Wasteland Workshop, Far Harbor and More|publisher=[[Bethesda Game Studios]]|date=February 16, 2016|access-date=July 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Everything You Need To Know About Fallout 4's DLC, Which Starts In March|url = http://kotaku.com/everything-you-need-to-know-about-fallout-4s-dlc-which-1759396375|website = Kotaku|access-date = February 16, 2016|language = en-US|first = Patricia|last = Hernandez}}</ref> The first add-on, ''[[Fallout 4: Automatron|Automatron]]'', which allows the player to build their custom robot companion by using robot parts while adding additional quests, was released to the European and North American markets on March 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/heres-exactly-when-fallout-4-automatron-expansion-/1100-6435861/|title=Here's Exactly When Fallout 4 Automatron Expansion Unlocks|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=March 21, 2016|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref> This was followed by ''Wasteland Workshop'' on April 12, 2016, which introduces new build options for settlements and the ability for the player to put captured creatures or humans in a cage, and adds new decorations like neon lights and lettering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/at-5-fallout-4s-wasteland-workshop-is-barely-worth-it/|title=At $5, Fallout 4's Wasteland Workshop is barely worth it|first=Christopher|last=Livington|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=April 23, 2016|accessdate=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/fallout-4s-next-dlc-drops-apri-12th-lets-you-collect-m-1769099023|title=Fallout 4's Next DLC Drops April 12th, Lets You Collect Monsters Like Pok\u00e9mon|last=Hernandez|first=Patricia|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The third add-on, titled ''[[Fallout 4: Far Harbor|Far Harbor]]'', is a story expansion set in the post-war city of [[Bar Harbor, Maine|Far Harbor, Maine]], and was released on May 19, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/2/16/11018046/fallout-4-dlc-schedule-prices-season-pass|title=Fallout 4 getting three add-ons this spring and more later, season pass price going up|first=Samit|last=Sarker|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4s-massive-far-harbor-expansion-gets-relea/1100-6439484/|title=Fallout 4's Massive Far Harbor Expansion Gets Release Date, New Trailer|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"ForbesBarHarbor\">{{cite web|last1=Thier|first1=Dave|title=The Real Bar Harbor Couldn't Be Happier About Fallout 4's 'Far Harbor'|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidthier/2016/05/12/the-real-bar-harbor-couldnt-be-happier-about-fallout-4s-far-harbor/#3cff19425189|website=forbes.com|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> On June 12, 2016, at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016|E3 2016]], Bethesda revealed three new add-on packages for the game; the first two, ''Contraptions Workshop'', released on June 21, 2016, and ''Vault-Tec Workshop'', released on July 26, 2016, are structured similarly to the ''Wasteland Workshop'' add-on, offering the player more build options and decorations; the ''Vault-Tec Workshop'' also adds a brief narrative. ''Fallout 4''{{'}}s third add-on, ''[[Fallout 4: Nuka-World|Nuka-World]]'', which was released on August 30, 2016, adds an amusement park-based area for the player to explore, in which the player can either side with or put an end to various raider groups residing in the park. If the player decides to do the former, they can help one of the raider groups take control of various settlements in the Commonwealth from the base game.<ref name=\"ign_e3_dlc\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2016/06/13/e3-2016-new-fallout-4-dlc-revealed | title=E3 2016: New Fallout 4 DLC revealed | work=[[IGN]] | publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] | first=Daniel | last=Krupa | date=June 12, 2016 | accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"final_dlc\">{{cite web | url=https://bethesda.net/en/article/2qUmCAJpNOoOEUiECOmWwa/fallout-4-contraptions-workshop-vault-tec-workshop-and-nuka-world | title=Fallout 4 \u2013 Contraptions Workshop, Vault-Tec Workshop, and Nuka-World | work=[[Bethesda Game Studios]] | publisher=[[Bethesda Softworks]] | date=June 12, 2016 | accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Creation Club ===\n{{main|Creation Club}}\nAt [[E3 2017]], Bethesda announced that ''Fallout 4'' would support Creation Club, an in-game support system to purchase and download custom content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/06/12/e3-2017-bethesda-introduces-creation-club-for-fallout-4-and-skyrim|title=E3 2017: Bethesda Introduces Creation Club For Fallout 4 and Skyrim|first=Chloi|last=Rad|date=June 11, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref> Creation Club went live in August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/8/28/16216326/fallout-4-creation-club-live-pc-ps4-xbox-one|title=Fallout 4 Creation Club goes live, and yes there is horse armor|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|date=August 28, 2017|website=Polygon|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{overquotation|section|date=December 2017}}\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = wikidata\n| Destruct = 7.5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-fallout-4-318096.phtml |title=Review: Fallout 4 |publisher=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| EGM = 9/10<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Buchholtz |first=Matt |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/fallout-4-review/ |title=Fallout 4 review |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |access-date=November 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110191114/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/fallout-4-review/ |archive-date=November 10, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| GI = 9/10<ref name=\"Game Informer review\">{{cite magazine |last=Reiner |first=Andrew |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/fallout_4/b/xboxone/archive/2015/11/09/a-familiar-wasteland.aspx |title=A Familiar Wasteland \u2013 Fallout 4 \u2013 Xbox One |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Tan |first=Nick |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/fallout-4 |title=Fallout 4 Review |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 9/10<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/fallout-4-review/1900-6416306/ |title=Fallout 4 Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Hurley |first=Leon |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/fallout-4-review/ |title=Fallout 4 review |publisher=[[GamesRadar]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| GT = 9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Moore |first=Ben |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/7472vc/fallout-4-review |title=Fallout 4 Review |publisher=[[GameTrailers]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| GB = (PC) {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |date=November 10, 2015 |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/reviews/fallout-4-pc-review/1900-726/ |title=Fallout 4 (PC) Review |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref><br />(Consoles) {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |date=November 10, 2015 |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/reviews/fallout-4-ps4-xone-review/1900-727/ |title=Fallout 4 (PS4, XONE) Review |publisher=[[Giant Bomb]] |accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.5/10<ref name=\"IGN review\">{{cite web |last=Stapleton |first=Dan |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/11/09/fallout-4-review |title=Fallout 4 Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 88/100<ref name=\"PCGUS\">{{cite magazine |last=Savage |first=Phil |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/fallout-4-review/ |title=Fallout 4 review |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| Poly = 9.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=Gies |first=Arthur |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/11/9/9648824/fallout-4-review-xbox-one-PS4-PC |title=Fallout 4 review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| VG = 9/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Miller |first=Simon |date=November 9, 2015 |url=http://www.videogamer.com/reviews/fallout_4_review.html |title=Fallout 4 Review |work=VideoGamer.com |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n''Fallout 4'' received \"generally favorable\" reviews on all three platforms according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].\n\n[[GameSpot]]'s Peter Brown awarded it a score of 9 out of 10, saying \"''Fallout 4'' is an argument for substance over style, and an excellent addition to the revered open-world series.\" Brown praised the \"thought-provoking\" narrative, \"intuitive\" creation tools, the large amount of content, the overall combat, and the overall freedom the player is given.<ref name=\"GSpot\"/> ''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s Andrew Reiner scored the game a 9 out of 10 and said: \"Bethesda has created another game you can lose your life in. New experiences just keep coming, and you always have another perk to unlock.\" Reiner praised the \"vastly improved\" combat, the \"denser\" world, and the \"brilliant\" score, but had mixed feelings about the visuals.<ref name=\"Game Informer review\" /> Dan Stapleton of [[IGN]] scored the game a 9.5 out of 10 and wrote: \"The world, exploration, crafting, atmosphere, and story of ''Fallout 4'' are all key parts of this hugely successful sandbox role-playing game. Great new reasons to obsessively gather and hoard relics of happier times, strong companions, and sympathetic villains driving tough decisions make it an adventure I'll definitely replay and revisit. Even the technical shakiness that crops up here and there can't even begin to slow down its momentum.\"<ref name=\"IGN review\" />\n\nPhil Savage of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' mentioned that ''Fallout 4'' is \"a loving production. It's filled with care and attention to detail\" and that it was \"a pleasure to pick through the world\". He concluded his review stating \"many of ''Fallout 4''{{'}}s problems, like every Bethesda RPG before it, are a consequence of what makes them unforgettable\".<ref name=\"PCGUS\"/> [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] awarded it a score of 9.5 out of 10, saying \"''Fallout 4'' brings great gameplay to match its world and ambiance\".<ref name=\"Poly\" />  Destructoid gave the game a 7.5 out of 10, writing \"a lot of the franchise's signature problems have carried over directly into ''Fallout 4''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-fallout-4-318096.phtml|title=Review: Fallout 4|work=Destructoid}}</ref>\n\n=== Sales ===\n''Fallout 4'' sold 1.2 million copies on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] in its first 24 hours of release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.technobuffalo.com/2015/11/11/fallout-4-steam-sales-24-hours/ |title=Fallout 4 sells 1.2 million copies on Steam during first day |last=Davidson |first=Joey |date=November 11, 2015 |access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref> The game also sold more digital than physical copies on day one of launch.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://twinfinite.net/2016/02/fallout-4-sold-more-digital-than-retail-copies-day-one/|title = Fallout 4 Sold More Digital Than Retail Copies Day One|date = February 22, 2016|access-date = February 23, 2016|website = Twinfinite|last = Coone|first = Sharon}}</ref> With almost 470,000 concurrent Steam players on launch day, ''Fallout 4'' broke ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]''{{'}}s record for having the most concurrent online players in a Steam game not developed by [[Valve Corporation|Valve]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Nofuente|first=Kyle|date =November 11, 2015|URL=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/105353/20151111/fallout-4-breaks-grand-theft-auto-v-steam-concurrent-user-records-on-day-one.htm|publisher=Tech Times|title=''Fallout 4'' Breaks ''Grand Theft Auto V'' Steam Concurrent User Records On Day One}}</ref> Bethesda shipped 12 million units to retailers within the first 24 hours,<ref name=\"gssales\">{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Fallout 4 ships 12 million copies in one Day|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4-ships-12-million-copies-in-one-day/1100-6432277/|website=GameSpot|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref> grossing {{US$|750 million|long=no}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gaudiosi |first1=John |title='Fallout 4' generated over $750 million in 24 hours |url=https://fortune.com/2015/11/16/fallout4-is-quiet-best-seller/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |date=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2017, Pete Hines announced that ''Fallout 4'' had sold more copies over the same time period than ''Skyrim'', though he did not provide an official number.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fallout-4-surpasses-skyrim-to-become-bethesdas-mos/1100-6447621/ |title=Fallout 4 Surpasses Skyrim To Become Bethesda's Most Successful Game Ever |website=GameSpot |first=Eddie |last=Makuch |date=2017-02-08 |accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n''Fallout 4'' received numerous awards and nominations from gaming publications such as [[GameSpot]],<ref name=\"gamespotgoty\">{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/game-of-the-year/best-games-awards/ | title = The Best Games of 2015 | website = [[GameSpot]] | accessdate = February 24, 2016}}</ref> [[GamesRadar]],<ref>{{cite web | last = Blain | first = Louise | url = http://www.gamesradar.com/reader-voted-game-of-the-year-2015-weekly-wrap-up/ | title = Reader voted GOTY 2015 \u2013 The Weekly Wrap Up | website = [[GamesRadar+]] | date = December 25, 2015 | accessdate = February 7, 2016}}</ref> [[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]],<ref>{{cite web | author = EGM staff | url = http://www.egmnow.com/platforms/xbox_360/egms-best-of-2015-part-five-05-01/ | title = EGM's Best of 2015: Part Five: #05 ~ #01 | work = [[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] | publisher = EGM Media | date = December 31, 2015 | access-date = February 4, 2016 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20160216044528/http://www.egmnow.com/platforms/xbox_360/egms-best-of-2015-part-five-05-01/ | archive-date = February 16, 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref> [[Game Revolution]],<ref>{{cite web | author = Game Revolution staff | url = http://www.gamerevolution.com/features/12120-best-of-2015-awards | title = Best of 2015 Awards | publisher = [[Game Revolution]] | date = January 1, 2016 | accessdate = February 4, 2016}}</ref> [[IGN]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/wikis/best-of-2015/ | title = IGN's Best of 2015 | publisher = [[IGN]] | accessdate = February 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://uk-microsites.ign.com/ign-pca | title = IGN's Gamescom People's Choice Award | website = IGN\u2019s People\u2019s Choice Award | accessdate = February 5, 2016}}</ref> and many more. The game received a \"Game of the Year\" award from the 19th ceremony of the [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences]]\u2014also known as the the [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\u2014among numerous nominations for the award from [[The Game Awards]], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/what-to-play/the-telegraph-game-awards-2015/ | title = Telegraph Video Game Awards 2015 | newspaper = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | publisher = [[Telegraph Media Group]] | date = December 16, 2015 | accessdate = February 4, 2016 | location = London}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine | author = PC Gamer staff | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/best-setting-2015-fallout-4/ | title = Best Setting 2015 \u2014 Fallout 4 | magazine = [[PC Gamer]] | date = December 24, 2015 | accessdate = February 4, 2016}}</ref> IGN and more.<ref name=\"Game Critics Awards\">{{cite web | url = http://gamecriticsawards.com/2015winners.html | title = Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2015 (2015 Winners) | publisher = [[Game Critics Awards]] |accessdate = February 15, 2018}}</ref> It was also placed on various lists of the best games of 2015 in which GameSpot put it at sixth,<ref name=\"gamespotgoty\"/> GamesRadar at fourth,<ref name=\"gradar2015\">{{cite web | author = GamesRadar staff | url = https://www.gamesradar.com/best-games-2015/ | title = Game of the Year 2015 | website = [[GamesRadar+]] | date = December 31, 2015 | accessdate = February 24, 2016}}</ref> among others top lists. The game also received awards and nominations for Role-playing game of the year with it winning the award from Game Critics and D.I.C.E. with nominations from various other gaming publications.<ref name=\"Game Critics Awards\"/>{{Weasel inline|date=December 2017}} \n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|+ Awards and nominations for ''Fallout 4''\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Recipient(s) !! Result !! class=\"unsortable\" | Ref.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2015\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Game Critics Awards#cite note-2|Game Critic Awards]] 2015\n| Best of Show\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"Game Critics Awards\" />\n|-\n| Best PC Game\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Role Playing Game\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards#2015|33rd Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"Golden Joystick 2015\">{{cite web | last = Hurley | first = Leon | url = http://www.gamesradar.com/golden-joysticks-all-winners-year/ | title = The Golden Joystick Awards: all the winners this year | website = [[GamesRadar+]] | date = October 30, 2015 | accessdate = December 5, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[The Game Awards]] [[The Game Awards 2015|2015]]\n| Game of the Year\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"TGA: Nominees\">{{cite web | url = http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ | title = Nominees {{!}} The Game Awards 2015 | website = [[The Game Awards]] | publisher = [[Ola Balola]] | date = November 12, 2015 | access-date = November 13, 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151114024126/http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ | archive-date = November 14, 2015 | url-status = dead}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Score/Soundtrack\n| Inon Zur\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Role Playing Game\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"33\" | 2016\n| rowspan=\"5\" |19th Annual [[Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences|D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Game of the Year\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web | last=Makuch | first = Eddie | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rise-of-the-tomb-raider-leads-dice-awards-with-9-n/1100-6433765/ | title = Rise of the Tomb Raider Leads D.I.C.E. Awards With 9 Nominations | work = GameSpot | date = January 13, 2016 | accessdate = January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Game Direction\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Story\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Role-playing/Massively Multiplayer Game of the Year\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement in Game Design\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |16th [[Game Developers Choice Awards]]\n| [[Game Developers Choice Award for Game of the Year|Game of the Year]]\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"GameDevelopersAwards\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamechoiceawards.com/archive/gdca_16th.html | title = 16th Annual Game Developers Choice Awards | publisher = [[Game Developers Choice Awards]] | accessdate = February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Design\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Technology\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2016 [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] Gaming Awards\n| Game of the Year\n| ''Fallout 4''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" s