{"title_page": "Croatia in the Eurovision Song Contest", "text_new": "{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = Croatia\n| Other names = \u25c4 [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]]\n| Member station = [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT)\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = National final\n | '''Dora'''\n | 1993\u20132011\n | 2019-2020\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal selection\n | 2012\u20132013\n | 2016\u20132018\n}}\n| ESC apps = 25 (18 finals)\n| ESC first = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993]]\n| ESC last = \n| ESC best = 4th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1999|1999]]\n| ESC worst = 17th <small>SF</small>: [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n| Website = [https://dora.hrt.hr HRT page on ''Dora'']\n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/croatia\n| Current = 2019\n}}\n\n[[Croatia]] has participated in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] 25 times since making its debut at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993 contest]]. Between 1993 and 2011, the Croatian entrant was selected at the ''Dora'' pop festival, an event organised by the national public broadcaster [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT). Croatia's best result in the contest is a fourth-place finish in {{escyr|1996}} and {{escyr|1999}}.\n\nCroatia achieved six top ten results in seven years, with [[Magazin]] & [[Lidija Horvat-Dunjko|Lidija]] sixth ({{escyr|1995}}), [[Maja Blagdan]] fourth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]]), former Magazin member [[Danijela Martinovic]] fifth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|1998]]), [[Doris Dragovi\u0107]] (who was 11th for [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]] in {{escyr|1986}}) fourth ({{escyr|1999}}), [[Goran Karan]] ninth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2000|2000]]), and [[Vanna (singer)|Vanna]] tenth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2001|2001]]). Since then, Croatia has failed to reach the top ten.\n\nCroatia failed to reach the final for four years in succession (2010\u201313), before choosing to not participate in {{Escyr|2014}} and {{escyr|2015}}<ref name=\"2014 withdrawal\"/><ref name=Eurovision2015>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Croatia: HRT will not participate Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86890/croatia-hrt-eurovision-2015|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=26 September 2014|date=26 September 2014}}</ref>. Croatia returned and reached the final in both {{escyr|2016}} and {{escyr|2017}}, but has now failed to reach the final in seven of the last 11 contests it has entered.\n\n==History==\nTen representatives of [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]] came from Croatia: in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969|1969]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1971|1971]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1986|1986]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988|1988]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990|1990]]. Apart from being the most successful Yugoslav republic in the contest, it gave the [[socialist]] republic its only win, \"[[Rock Me (Riva song)|Rock Me]]\", sung by [[Riva (band)|Riva]] in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]], that was held in [[Lausanne]]. The [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990]] was held in [[Zagreb]] as a result.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=306 | title=Eurovision Song Contest 1990 | work=eurovision.tv | publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] | accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the dissolution of Yugoslavia in 1991, the Croatian national public broadcaster [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT) had organised a festival to select a Croatian representative for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992|1992 Contest]]. If HRT had been a member of the EBU in time for the contest, the first Croatian entry at Eurovision would have been the band [[Magazin]] with \"Aleluja\".<ref>[http://free-st.t-com.hr/eurodalmatia/gotovo_za_web/dora/results/1992.htm Croatian Contest for the Eurovision Song Contest - Grand Prix '92] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403045549/http://free-st.t-com.hr/eurodalmatia/gotovo_za_web/dora/results/1992.htm |date=April 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nCroatia's first entry as an independent state was in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993]] with the band [[Put (band)|Put]], performing \"[[Don't Ever Cry]]\" which was, despite the [[English language|English]] title, also partially performed in [[Croatian language|Croatian]]. The song came third in the ''[[Kvalifikacija za Millstreet|Qualification for Millstreet]]'' pre-selection event, which allowed their participation in the 1993 contest. Croatia's best position, as of 2020, has been with [[Maja Blagdan]]'s [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]] entry \"[[Sveta ljubav]]\" and [[Doris Dragovi\u0107]]'s [[Eurovision Song Contest 1999|1999]] entry \"[[Marija Magdalena]]\".{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nAlong with Malta, Cyprus and Portugal, Croatia was never relegated in the 1990s, and, unlike Cyprus and Portugal, it was never relegated in the beginning of the 21st century. Relegation meant that the country would have to sit out the subsequent contest due to poor placement.\n\nCroatian broadcaster HRT announced on 19 September 2013 that they would not participate in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]] contest, citing the financial difficulties, as well as a string of poor results between {{Escyr|2010}} and {{Escyr|2013}} influencing their decision to take a year's break. The last time Croatia qualified for the grand final was in {{Escyr|2009}}.<ref name=\"2014 withdrawal\">{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Croatia: HRT will not participate in Eurovision 2014|url=http://www.esctoday.com/68223/croatia-hrt-will-participate-eurovision-2014/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=19 September 2013|date=19 September 2013}}</ref> Croatia would not return to the contest in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]],<ref name=Eurovision2015/> and on 5 May 2015, HRT announced that it wouldn't broadcast the 2015 contest either.<ref>{{cite web|title=HRT ne prenosi Eurosong 2015.!'|url=http://eurosong.hr/hrt-ne-prenosi-jubilarni-eurosong-2015/|language=Croatian|website=eurosong.hr|accessdate=6 May 2015|date=5 May 2015}}</ref> It was the first time since [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992|1992]] for HRT to not broadcast the contest.\n\nOn 26 November 2015, it was announced that Croatia would return to the contest in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Croatia: HRT confirms participation in Eurovision 2016|url=http://esctoday.com/106089/croatia-hrt-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2016/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=26 November 2015|date=26 November 2015}}</ref> It was also reported that the entry would possibly be the winner of the first season of the [[The Voice \u2013 Najljep\u0161i glas Hrvatske|Croatian version of ''The Voice'']].<ref>{{cite news|first=Tina|last=Premec|title=ZA NAJSKUPLJI SHOW HTV-a PRIJAVILO SE VI\u0160E OD 1000 LJUDI 'Koliko smo ga platili? To je tajna'|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/the-voice-za-najskuplji-show-htv-a-prijavilo-se-vise-od-1000-ljudi/1225371/|language=Croatian|newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]]|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=7 October 2014}}</ref> [[Nina Kralji\u0107]] won ''The Voice'' and was selected to represent Croatia with the internally selected song \"[[Lighthouse (Nina Kralji\u0107 song)|Lighthouse]]\". The entry qualified for the final, making it the first time Croatia had made it to the final since 2009. After the successful return in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]], Croatian national broadcaster HRT confirmed on 17 September 2016 that they would also participate in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=B\u0142a\u017cewicz|first1=Maciej|title=Croatia confirms Eurovision 2017 participation|url=http://escbubble.com/en/2016/09/croatia-confirms-eurovision-2017-participation/|website=escbubble.com|accessdate=17 September 2016|date=17 September 2016}}</ref> [[Jacques Houdek]], the coach of Nina Kralji\u0107 in ''The Voice - Najljep\u0161i glas Hrvatske'', was internally selected to represent the country on 17 February 2017, exactly five months after they confirmed the participation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eurosong.hrt.hr/vijest/53/jacques-houdek-predstavlja-hrvatsku-na-natjecanju-|title=Eurosong - Jacques Houdek predstavlja Hrvatsku na natjecanju za pjesmu Eurovizije u Ukrajini|last=|first=|date=17 February 2017|newspaper=eurosong.hrt.hr|access-date=17 February 2017|work=|language=hr|via=}}</ref>\nOn 30 October 2018, it was announced by HRT that the national final, ''Dora'', would return in 2019, traditionally taking place in [[Opatija]], a famous summer resort. The Croatian entry for [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019]] was selected on 16 February.<ref>https://eurosong.hr/hrt-potvrdio-dobro-dosla-dora-2019/</ref>\n\n== Contestants ==\nThe Yugoslavian entries in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969|1969]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1971|1971]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1986|1986]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988|1988]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990|1990]] were from Croatia and competed for [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FC3\"|{{center|1}}\n|Winner\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#CCC\"|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#C96\"|{{center|3}}\n|Third place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FE8080\"|\u25c1\n|Last place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#A4EAA9\"|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete \n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!width=50px|Final\n!width=50px|Points\n!width=50px|Semi\n!width=50px|Points \n|-\n!{{Escyr|1993}}\n|[[Put (band)|Put]]\n|[[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[English language|English]]\n|\"[[Don't Ever Cry]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|31\n|bgcolor=\"CC9966\" align=center|3\n|bgcolor=\"CC9966\" align=center|51\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1994}}\n|[[Tony Cetinski]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Nek' ti bude ljubav sva]]\"\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|27\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"99999\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1995}}\n|[[Magazin]] & [[Lidija Horvat-Dunjko|Lidija]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Nostalgija]]\"\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|91\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1996}}\n|[[Maja Blagdan]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Sveta ljubav]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|98\n|align=center|19\n|align=center|30\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1997}}\n|[[E.N.I. (band)|E.N.I.]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Probudi me]]\"\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|24\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"7\" data-sort-value=\"99999\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1998}}\n|[[Danijela Martinovi\u0107|Danijela]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Neka mi ne svane]]\"\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|131{{ref|a|1}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1999}}\n|[[Doris Dragovi\u0107]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Marija Magdalena]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|118\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2000}}\n|[[Goran Karan]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Kad zaspu an\u0111eli]]\"\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|70\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2001}}\n|[[Vanna (singer)|Vanna]]\n|English\n|\"[[Strings of My Heart]]\"\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|42\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2002}}\n|[[Vesna Pisarovi\u0107]]\n|English\n|\"[[Everything I Want]]\"\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|44\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2003}}\n|[[Claudia Beni]]\n|Croatian, English\n|\"[[Vi\u0161e nisam tvoja]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|29\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2004}}\n|[[Ivan Mikuli\u0107]]\n|English\n|\"[[You Are the Only One (Ivan Mikuli\u0107 song)|You Are The Only One]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|50\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|72\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2005}}\n|[[Boris Novkovi\u0107]] feat. [[LADO (folk ensemble)|Lado members]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Vukovi umiru sami]]\"\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|115\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|169\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2006}}\n|[[Severina Vu\u010dkovi\u0107|Severina]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Moja \u0161tikla]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|56 \n|colspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"-9999\" {{N/A|Top 11 Previous Year}}{{efn|name=note2|According to the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|then-Eurovision rules]], the top ten non-[[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big Four]] countries from the previous year along with the Big Four automatically qualified for the Grand Final without having to compete in semi-finals. For example, if Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the 11th and 12th spots were advanced to next year's Grand Final along with all countries ranked in the top ten.}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2007}}\n|[[Dragonfly (Croatia)|Dragonfly]] feat. [[Dado Topi\u0107]]\n|Croatian, English\n|\"[[Vjerujem u ljubav]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|54\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2008}}\n|[[Kraljevi ulice]] & [[75 cents|75 Cents]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Romanca]]\"\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|44\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|112\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2009}}\n|[[Igor Cukrov]] feat. [[Andrea \u0160u\u0161njara|Andrea]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Lijepa Tena]]\"\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|45\n|align=center|13{{ref|b|2}}\n|align=center|33\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2010}}\n|[[Feminnem]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Lako je sve]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|33\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2011}}\n|[[Daria Kinzer|Daria]]\n|English\n|\"[[Celebrate (Daria Kinzer song)|Celebrate]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|41\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012}}\n|[[Nina Badri\u0107]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Nebo (Nina Badri\u0107 song)|Nebo]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|42\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2013}}\n|[[Klapa s Mora]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Mi\u017eerja]]\"\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|38\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate in {{ESCYr|2014}} and {{ESCYr|2015}}}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2016}}\n|[[Nina Kralji\u0107]]\n|English\n|\"[[Lighthouse (Nina Kralji\u0107 song)|Lighthouse]]\"\n|align=center|23\n|align=center|73\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|133\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2017}}\n|[[Jacques Houdek]]\n|English, [[Italian language|Italian]]\n|\"[[My Friend (Jacques Houdek song)|My Friend]]\"\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|128\n|align=center|8\n|align=center|141\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2018}}\n|[[Franka Bateli\u0107|Franka]]\n|English\n|\"[[Crazy (Franka Bateli\u0107 song)|Crazy]]\"\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|63\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2019}}\n|[[Roko Bla\u017eevi\u0107|Roko]]\n|English, Croatian\n|\"[[The Dream (Roko Bla\u017eevi\u0107 song)|The Dream]]\"\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|64\n|-bgcolor=\"#A4EAA9\"\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|2020}}}}{{Efn|The 2020 contest was cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|[[Damir Ked\u017eo]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Divlji vjetre]]\"\n|colspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Contest cancelled}} '''X'''\n|}\n;<small>'''NOTES''':\n:1. {{note|a}} Spain originally gave its 12 points to Israel and 10 to Norway. After the broadcast it was announced that Spanish broadcaster wrongly tallied the votes and Germany should have got the top mark - 12 points - instead of being snubbed, as it happened. The mistake was corrected and so Germany was placed 7th over Norway. Israel and Norway both received 2 points less than originally and Croatia, Malta, Portugal, United Kingdom, Netherlands, Belgium, Estonia and Turkey all received one point less than indicated during the broadcast.\n:2. {{note|b}} In 2009, Croatia qualified through the back-up jury selection. \n:3. If a country had won the previous year, they did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year. In addition from 2004-2007, the top ten countries who were not members of the big four did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year. If, for example, Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the countries who placed 11th and 12th were advanced to the following year's grand final along with the rest of the top ten countries. Serbia & Montenegro decided to withdraw from the competition even tho they finished in the top ten the previous year, so the country that placed 11th (which was Croatia) got the spot in the final instead.</small>\n\n==Awards==\n===Barbara Dex Award===\n{{further|Barbara Dex Award}}\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!Year\n!Performer\n!Host city\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n|[[Nina Kralji\u0107]]\n|{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Stockholm]]\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2016/05/22/barbara-dex-award-2016-nina-kraljic-wins-eurovisions-worst-dressed/142524/|title=Barbara Dex Award 2016: Croatia\u2019s Nina Kraljic tops Eurovision\u2019s Worst Dressed list|publisher=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=22 May 2016|accessdate=8 December 2019|first=William Lee|last=Adams}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Related involvement==\n===Heads of delegation===\nThe public broadcaster of each participating country in the Eurovision Song Contest assigns a head of delegation as the EBU's contact person and the leader of their delegation at the event. The delegation, whose size can greatly vary, includes a head of press, the contestants, songwriters, composers and backing vocalists, among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/organisers/heads-of-delegation/|title=Heads of Delegation|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Year\n!Head of delegation\n!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|\u017deljen Kla\u0161terka\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/01/17/croatia-dora-2019-participants-revealed/|title=Croatia: Dora 2019 Participants Revealed|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019|website=eurovision.tv|first=Neil|last=Farren}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2020}}\n|Ur\u0161ula Tolj\n|{{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/12/10/croatia-ursula-tolj-announced-as-head-of-delegation/|title=Croatia: Ur\u0161ula Tolj Announced As Head of Delegation|last=Granger|first=Anthony|date=2019-12-10|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n===Commentators and spokespersons===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!TV commentator\n!TV channel\n!Radio commentator (HR 2)\n!Spokesperson\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1992}}\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1993}}\n|rowspan=\"8\" |Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov\n|[[HRT 2]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|Veljko \u0110ureti\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1994}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[HRT 1]]\n|[[Helga Vlahovi\u0107]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1995}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Daniela Trbovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1996}}\n|HRT 2\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Draginja Bala\u0161\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1997}}\n|rowspan=\"5\" |HRT 1\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Davor Me\u0161trovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1998}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1999}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Marko Ra\u0161ica\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2000}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2001}}\n|Ante Batinovi\u0107\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Draginja Bala\u0161\n|Daniela Trbovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2002}}\n|[[Oliver Mlakar]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |HRT 2\n|[[Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|Daniela Trbovi\u0107\n|Davor Me\u0161trovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov\n|rowspan=\"9\" |HRT 1\n|rowspan=\"9\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Barbara Kolar]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2005}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2006}}\n|rowspan=\"8\"|Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107\n|[[Mila Horvat]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Barbara Kolar\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Mila Horvat\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Nevena Rendeli\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\n|HRT 2 {{small|(semi-finals)}}<br>HRT 1 {{small|(final)}}\n|Robert Urli\u0107\n|Ur\u0161ula Tolj\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}{{Efn|In 2014, HRT screened only the grand final. The semi-finals were not screened.}}\n|Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov\n|HRT 1\n|Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov \n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|{{center|<ref>http://www.tportal.hr/showtime/glazba/331670/HRT-ov-komentar-Eurosonga-bio-uvredljivo-los.html</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2015}}\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107\n|rowspan=\"4\" |HRT 1\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Zlatko Turkalj Turki\n|Nevena Rendeli\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2017}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Ur\u0161ula Tolj\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|Monika Lelas Halambek\n|\n|}\n\n* From {{Escyr|1961}} until {{Escyr|1991}}, Croatia competed as part of {{Esccnty|Yugoslavia}}.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:ESC 2007 Croatia - Dragonfly & Dado Topic - Vjerujem u ljubav.jpg|[[Dragonfly (band)|Dragonfly]] feat. [[Dado Topi\u0107]] at Helsinki ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]])\nFile:Croatia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008.jpg|[[Kraljevi ulice]] & [[75 cents|75 Cents]] at Belgrade ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]])\nFile:Igor Cukrov & Andrea \u0160u\u0161njara (3830890311).jpg|[[Igor Cukrov]] feat. [[Andrea \u0160u\u0161njara|Andrea]] at Moscow ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]])\nFile:Feminnem - Lako je sve (2nd Semi-final).jpg|[[Feminnem]] at Oslo ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]])\nFile:\u041d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u0434\u0440\u0438\u0447.JPG| [[Nina Badri\u0107]] at Baku ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]])\nFile:ESC2013 - Croatia 03.jpg|[[Klapa s Mora]] at Malm\u00f6 ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]])\nFile:ESC2016 - Croatia 23 (zoom).jpg|[[Nina Kralji\u0107]] at Stockholm ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]])\nFile:Eurovision Song Contest 2017, Semi Final 2 Rehearsals. Photo 223.jpg|[[Jacques Houdek]] at Kyiv ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]])\nFile:ESC2018 - Croatia 01.jpg|[[Franka Bateli\u0107|Franka]] at Lisbon ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]])\nFile:ESC2019-Croatia.jpg|[[Roko Bla\u017eevi\u0107|Roko]] at Tel Aviv ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Croatia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n*[[Dora Peja\u010devi\u0107]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090818124200/http://www.hrt.hr/dora/ \"Dora\" - Croatian ESC Pre-selection]\n*[https://eurosong.hr/povijest/povijest-dore/ Povijest Dore] {{in lang|hr}} ''eurosong.hr''\n\n{{Croatia in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Music of Croatia}}\n\n[[Category:Music festivals in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Croatia in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = Croatia\n| Other names = \u25c4 [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]]\n| Member station = [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT)\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = National final\n | '''Dora'''\n | 1993\u20132011\n | 2019-2020\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal selection\n | 2012\u20132013\n | 2016\u20132018\n}}\n| ESC apps = 25 (18 finals)\n| ESC first = [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993]]\n| ESC last = \n| ESC best = 4th: [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1999|1999]]\n| ESC worst = 17th <small>SF</small>: [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n| Website = [https://dora.hrt.hr HRT page on ''Dora'']\n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/croatia\n| Current = 2019\n}}\n\n[[Croatia]] has participated in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] 25 times since making its debut at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993 contest]]. Between 1993 and 2011, the Croatian entrant was selected at the ''Dora'' pop festival, an event organised by the national public broadcaster [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT). Croatia's best result in the contest is a fourth-place finish in {{escyr|1996}} and {{escyr|1999}}.\n\nCroatia achieved six top ten results in seven years, with [[Magazin]] & [[Lidija Horvat-Dunjko|Lidija]] sixth ({{escyr|1995}}), [[Maja Blagdan]] fourth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]]), former Magazin member [[Danijela Martinovic]] fifth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 1998|1998]]), [[Doris Dragovi\u0107]] (who was 11th for [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]] in {{escyr|1986}}) fourth ({{escyr|1999}}), [[Goran Karan]] ninth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2000|2000]]), and [[Vanna (singer)|Vanna]] tenth ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2001|2001]]). Since then, Croatia has failed to reach the top ten.\n\nCroatia failed to reach the final for four years in succession (2010\u201313), before choosing to not participate in {{Escyr|2014}} and {{escyr|2015}}<ref name=\"2014 withdrawal\"/><ref name=Eurovision2015>{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Croatia: HRT will not participate Eurovision 2015|url=http://esctoday.com/86890/croatia-hrt-eurovision-2015|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=26 September 2014|date=26 September 2014}}</ref>. Croatia returned and reached the final in both {{escyr|2016}} and {{escyr|2017}}, but has now failed to reach the final in seven of the last 11 contests it has entered.\n\n==History==\nTen representatives of [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]] came from Croatia: in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969|1969]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1971|1971]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1986|1986]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988|1988]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990|1990]]. Apart from being the most successful Yugoslav republic in the contest, it gave the [[socialist]] republic its only win, \"[[Rock Me (Riva song)|Rock Me]]\", sung by [[Riva (band)|Riva]] in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]], that was held in [[Lausanne]]. The [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990]] was held in [[Zagreb]] as a result.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=306 | title=Eurovision Song Contest 1990 | work=eurovision.tv | publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]] | accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the dissolution of Yugoslavia in 1991, the Croatian national public broadcaster [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT) had organised a festival to select a Croatian representative for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992|1992 Contest]]. If HRT had been a member of the EBU in time for the contest, the first Croatian entry at Eurovision would have been the band [[Magazin]] with \"Aleluja\".<ref>[http://free-st.t-com.hr/eurodalmatia/gotovo_za_web/dora/results/1992.htm Croatian Contest for the Eurovision Song Contest - Grand Prix '92] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403045549/http://free-st.t-com.hr/eurodalmatia/gotovo_za_web/dora/results/1992.htm |date=April 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nCroatia's first entry as an independent state was in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993|1993]] with the band [[Put (band)|Put]], performing \"[[Don't Ever Cry]]\" which was, despite the [[English language|English]] title, also partially performed in [[Croatian language|Croatian]]. The song came third in the ''[[Kvalifikacija za Millstreet|Qualification for Millstreet]]'' pre-selection event, which allowed their participation in the 1993 contest. Croatia's best position, as of 2020, has been with [[Maja Blagdan]]'s [[Eurovision Song Contest 1996|1996]] entry \"[[Sveta ljubav]]\" and [[Doris Dragovi\u0107]]'s [[Eurovision Song Contest 1999|1999]] entry \"[[Marija Magdalena]]\".{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nAlong with Malta, Cyprus and Portugal, Croatia was never relegated in the 1990s, and, unlike Cyprus and Portugal, it was never relegated in the beginning of the 21st century. Relegation meant that the country would have to sit out the subsequent contest due to poor placement.\n\nCroatian broadcaster HRT announced on 19 September 2013 that they would not participate in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]] contest, citing the financial difficulties, as well as a string of poor results between {{Escyr|2010}} and {{Escyr|2013}} influencing their decision to take a year's break. The last time Croatia qualified for the grand final was in {{Escyr|2009}}.<ref name=\"2014 withdrawal\">{{cite web|last=Jiandani|first=Sanjay|title=Croatia: HRT will not participate in Eurovision 2014|url=http://www.esctoday.com/68223/croatia-hrt-will-participate-eurovision-2014/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=19 September 2013|date=19 September 2013}}</ref> Croatia would not return to the contest in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]],<ref name=Eurovision2015/> and on 5 May 2015, HRT announced that it wouldn't broadcast the 2015 contest either.<ref>{{cite web|title=HRT ne prenosi Eurosong 2015.!'|url=http://eurosong.hr/hrt-ne-prenosi-jubilarni-eurosong-2015/|language=Croatian|website=eurosong.hr|accessdate=6 May 2015|date=5 May 2015}}</ref> It was the first time since [[Eurovision Song Contest 1992|1992]] for HRT to not broadcast the contest.\n\nOn 26 November 2015, it was announced that Croatia would return to the contest in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sanjay|last=Jiandani|title=Croatia: HRT confirms participation in Eurovision 2016|url=http://esctoday.com/106089/croatia-hrt-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2016/|publisher=ESCToday|website=esctoday.com|accessdate=26 November 2015|date=26 November 2015}}</ref> It was also reported that the entry would possibly be the winner of the first season of the [[The Voice \u2013 Najljep\u0161i glas Hrvatske|Croatian version of ''The Voice'']].<ref>{{cite news|first=Tina|last=Premec|title=ZA NAJSKUPLJI SHOW HTV-a PRIJAVILO SE VI\u0160E OD 1000 LJUDI 'Koliko smo ga platili? To je tajna'|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/the-voice-za-najskuplji-show-htv-a-prijavilo-se-vise-od-1000-ljudi/1225371/|language=Croatian|newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]]|accessdate=6 October 2014|date=7 October 2014}}</ref> [[Nina Kralji\u0107]] won ''The Voice'' and was selected to represent Croatia with the internally selected song \"[[Lighthouse (Nina Kralji\u0107 song)|Lighthouse]]\". The entry qualified for the final, making it the first time Croatia had made it to the final since 2009. After the successful return in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]], Croatian national broadcaster HRT confirmed on 17 September 2016 that they would also participate in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=B\u0142a\u017cewicz|first1=Maciej|title=Croatia confirms Eurovision 2017 participation|url=http://escbubble.com/en/2016/09/croatia-confirms-eurovision-2017-participation/|website=escbubble.com|accessdate=17 September 2016|date=17 September 2016}}</ref> [[Jacques Houdek]], the coach of Nina Kralji\u0107 in ''The Voice - Najljep\u0161i glas Hrvatske'', was internally selected to represent the country on 17 February 2017, exactly five months after they confirmed the participation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eurosong.hrt.hr/vijest/53/jacques-houdek-predstavlja-hrvatsku-na-natjecanju-|title=Eurosong - Jacques Houdek predstavlja Hrvatsku na natjecanju za pjesmu Eurovizije u Ukrajini|last=|first=|date=17 February 2017|newspaper=eurosong.hrt.hr|access-date=17 February 2017|work=|language=hr|via=}}</ref>\nOn 30 October 2018, it was announced by HRT that the national final, ''Dora'', would return in 2019, traditionally taking place in [[Opatija]], a famous summer resort. The Croatian entry for [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019]] was selected on 16 February.<ref>https://eurosong.hr/hrt-potvrdio-dobro-dosla-dora-2019/</ref>\n\n== Contestants ==\nThe Yugoslavian entries in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1963|1963]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968|1968]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969|1969]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1971|1971]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1972|1972]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1986|1986]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1987|1987]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1988|1988]], [[Eurovision Song Contest 1989|1989]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990|1990]] were from Croatia and competed for [[Yugoslavia in the Eurovision Song Contest|Yugoslavia]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FC3\"|{{center|1}}\n|Winner\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#CCC\"|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#C96\"|{{center|3}}\n|Third place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#FE8080\"|\u25c1\n|Last place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#A4EAA9\"|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete \n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!width=50px|Final\n!width=50px|Points\n!width=50px|Semi\n!width=50px|Points \n|-\n!{{Escyr|1993}}\n|[[Put (band)|Put]]\n|[[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[English language|English]]\n|\"[[Don't Ever Cry]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|31\n|bgcolor=\"CC9966\" align=center|3\n|bgcolor=\"CC9966\" align=center|51\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1994}}\n|[[Tony Cetinski]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Nek' ti bude ljubav sva]]\"\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|27\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"99999\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1995}}\n|[[Magazin]] & [[Lidija Horvat-Dunjko|Lidija]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Nostalgija]]\"\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|91\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1996}}\n|[[Maja Blagdan]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Sveta ljubav]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|98\n|align=center|19\n|align=center|30\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1997}}\n|[[E.N.I. (band)|E.N.I.]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Probudi me]]\"\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|24\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"7\" data-sort-value=\"99999\" {{N/A|No semi-finals}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1998}}\n|[[Danijela Martinovi\u0107|Danijela]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Neka mi ne svane]]\"\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|131{{ref|a|1}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|1999}}\n|[[Doris Dragovi\u0107]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Marija Magdalena]]\"\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|118\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2000}}\n|[[Goran Karan]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Kad zaspu an\u0111eli]]\"\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|70\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2001}}\n|[[Vanna (singer)|Vanna]]\n|English\n|\"[[Strings of My Heart]]\"\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|42\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2002}}\n|[[Vesna Pisarovi\u0107]]\n|English\n|\"[[Everything I Want]]\"\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|44\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2003}}\n|[[Claudia Beni]]\n|Croatian, English\n|\"[[Vi\u0161e nisam tvoja]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|29\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2004}}\n|[[Ivan Mikuli\u0107]]\n|English\n|\"[[You Are the Only One (Ivan Mikuli\u0107 song)|You Are The Only One]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|50\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|72\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2005}}\n|[[Boris Novkovi\u0107]] feat. [[LADO (folk ensemble)|Lado members]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Vukovi umiru sami]]\"\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|115\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|169\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2006}}\n|[[Severina Vu\u010dkovi\u0107|Severina]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Moja \u0161tikla]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|56 \n|colspan=\"2\" data-sort-value=\"-9999\" {{N/A|Top 11 Previous Year}}{{efn|name=note2|According to the [[Rules of the Eurovision Song Contest|then-Eurovision rules]], the top ten non-[[Eurovision Song Contest#Big Four and Big Five|Big Four]] countries from the previous year along with the Big Four automatically qualified for the Grand Final without having to compete in semi-finals. For example, if Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the 11th and 12th spots were advanced to next year's Grand Final along with all countries ranked in the top ten.}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2007}}\n|[[Dragonfly (Croatia)|Dragonfly]] feat. [[Dado Topi\u0107]]\n|Croatian, English\n|\"[[Vjerujem u ljubav]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|54\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2008}}\n|[[Kraljevi ulice]] & [[75 cents|75 Cents]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Romanca]]\"\n|align=center|21\n|align=center|44\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|112\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2009}}\n|[[Igor Cukrov]] feat. [[Andrea \u0160u\u0161njara|Andrea]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Lijepa Tena]]\"\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|45\n|align=center|13{{ref|b|2}}\n|align=center|33\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2010}}\n|[[Feminnem]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Lako je sve]]\"\n|colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|33\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2011}}\n|[[Daria Kinzer|Daria]]\n|English\n|\"[[Celebrate (Daria Kinzer song)|Celebrate]]\"\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|41\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012}}\n|[[Nina Badri\u0107]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Nebo (Nina Badri\u0107 song)|Nebo]]\"\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|42\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2013}}\n|[[Klapa s Mora]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Mi\u017eerja]]\"\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|38\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate in {{ESCYr|2014}} and {{ESCYr|2015}}}}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2016}}\n|[[Nina Kralji\u0107]]\n|English\n|\"[[Lighthouse (Nina Kralji\u0107 song)|Lighthouse]]\"\n|align=center|23\n|align=center|73\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|133\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2017}}\n|[[Jacques Houdek]]\n|English, [[Italian language|Italian]]\n|\"[[My Friend (Jacques Houdek song)|My Friend]]\"\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|128\n|align=center|8\n|align=center|141\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2018}}\n|[[Franka Bateli\u0107|Franka]]\n|English\n|\"[[Crazy (Franka Bateli\u0107 song)|Crazy]]\"\n|rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Failed to qualify}}\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|63\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2019}}\n|[[Roko Bla\u017eevi\u0107|Roko]]\n|English, Croatian\n|\"[[The Dream (Roko Bla\u017eevi\u0107 song)|The Dream]]\"\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|64\n|-bgcolor=\"#A4EAA9\"\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|2020}}}}{{Efn|2020 contest was cancelled due to 2019-20 pandemic of Coronavirus.}}\n|[[Damir Ked\u017eo]]\n|Croatian\n|\"[[Divlji vjetre]]\"\n|colspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Contest cancelled}} '''X'''\n|}\n;<small>'''NOTES''':\n:1. {{note|a}} Spain originally gave its 12 points to Israel and 10 to Norway. After the broadcast it was announced that Spanish broadcaster wrongly tallied the votes and Germany should have got the top mark - 12 points - instead of being snubbed, as it happened. The mistake was corrected and so Germany was placed 7th over Norway. Israel and Norway both received 2 points less than originally and Croatia, Malta, Portugal, United Kingdom, Netherlands, Belgium, Estonia and Turkey all received one point less than indicated during the broadcast.\n:2. {{note|b}} In 2009, Croatia qualified through the back-up jury selection. \n:3. If a country had won the previous year, they did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year. In addition from 2004-2007, the top ten countries who were not members of the big four did not have to compete in the semi-finals the following year. If, for example, Germany and France placed inside the top ten, the countries who placed 11th and 12th were advanced to the following year's grand final along with the rest of the top ten countries. Serbia & Montenegro decided to withdraw from the competition even tho they finished in the top ten the previous year, so the country that placed 11th (which was Croatia) got the spot in the final instead.</small>\n\n==Awards==\n===Barbara Dex Award===\n{{further|Barbara Dex Award}}\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!Year\n!Performer\n!Host city\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n|[[Nina Kralji\u0107]]\n|{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Stockholm]]\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2016/05/22/barbara-dex-award-2016-nina-kraljic-wins-eurovisions-worst-dressed/142524/|title=Barbara Dex Award 2016: Croatia\u2019s Nina Kraljic tops Eurovision\u2019s Worst Dressed list|publisher=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=22 May 2016|accessdate=8 December 2019|first=William Lee|last=Adams}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Related involvement==\n===Heads of delegation===\nThe public broadcaster of each participating country in the Eurovision Song Contest assigns a head of delegation as the EBU's contact person and the leader of their delegation at the event. The delegation, whose size can greatly vary, includes a head of press, the contestants, songwriters, composers and backing vocalists, among others.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/organisers/heads-of-delegation/|title=Heads of Delegation|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!Year\n!Head of delegation\n!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|\u017deljen Kla\u0161terka\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/01/17/croatia-dora-2019-participants-revealed/|title=Croatia: Dora 2019 Participants Revealed|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019|website=eurovision.tv|first=Neil|last=Farren}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2020}}\n|Ur\u0161ula Tolj\n|{{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/12/10/croatia-ursula-tolj-announced-as-head-of-delegation/|title=Croatia: Ur\u0161ula Tolj Announced As Head of Delegation|last=Granger|first=Anthony|date=2019-12-10|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n===Commentators and spokespersons===\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!TV commentator\n!TV channel\n!Radio commentator (HR 2)\n!Spokesperson\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1992}}\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1993}}\n|rowspan=\"8\" |Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov\n|[[HRT 2]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|Veljko \u0110ureti\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1994}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[HRT 1]]\n|[[Helga Vlahovi\u0107]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1995}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Daniela Trbovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1996}}\n|HRT 2\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Draginja Bala\u0161\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1997}}\n|rowspan=\"5\" |HRT 1\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Davor Me\u0161trovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1998}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1999}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Marko Ra\u0161ica\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2000}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2001}}\n|Ante Batinovi\u0107\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Draginja Bala\u0161\n|Daniela Trbovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2002}}\n|[[Oliver Mlakar]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" |HRT 2\n|[[Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2003}}\n|Daniela Trbovi\u0107\n|Davor Me\u0161trovi\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2004}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov\n|rowspan=\"9\" |HRT 1\n|rowspan=\"9\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Barbara Kolar]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2005}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2006}}\n|rowspan=\"8\"|Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107\n|[[Mila Horvat]]\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Barbara Kolar\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Mila Horvat\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Nevena Rendeli\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\n|HRT 2 {{small|(semi-finals)}}<br>HRT 1 {{small|(final)}}\n|Robert Urli\u0107\n|Ur\u0161ula Tolj\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}{{Efn|In 2014, HRT screened only the grand final. The semi-finals were not screened.}}\n|Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov\n|HRT 1\n|Aleksandar \"Aco\" Kostadinov \n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|{{center|<ref>http://www.tportal.hr/showtime/glazba/331670/HRT-ov-komentar-Eurosonga-bio-uvredljivo-los.html</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2015}}\n|colspan=\"2\" {{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107\n|rowspan=\"4\" |HRT 1\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Zlatko Turkalj Turki\n|Nevena Rendeli\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2017}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Ur\u0161ula Tolj\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Du\u0161ko \u010curli\u0107\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|Monika Lelas Halambek\n|\n|}\n\n* From {{Escyr|1961}} until {{Escyr|1991}}, Croatia competed as part of {{Esccnty|Yugoslavia}}.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:ESC 2007 Croatia - Dragonfly & Dado Topic - Vjerujem u ljubav.jpg|[[Dragonfly (band)|Dragonfly]] feat. [[Dado Topi\u0107]] at Helsinki ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]])\nFile:Croatia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008.jpg|[[Kraljevi ulice]] & [[75 cents|75 Cents]] at Belgrade ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]])\nFile:Igor Cukrov & Andrea \u0160u\u0161njara (3830890311).jpg|[[Igor Cukrov]] feat. [[Andrea \u0160u\u0161njara|Andrea]] at Moscow ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]])\nFile:Feminnem - Lako je sve (2nd Semi-final).jpg|[[Feminnem]] at Oslo ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2010|2010]])\nFile:\u041d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0430\u0434\u0440\u0438\u0447.JPG| [[Nina Badri\u0107]] at Baku ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]])\nFile:ESC2013 - Croatia 03.jpg|[[Klapa s Mora]] at Malm\u00f6 ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]])\nFile:ESC2016 - Croatia 23 (zoom).jpg|[[Nina Kralji\u0107]] at Stockholm ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]])\nFile:Eurovision Song Contest 2017, Semi Final 2 Rehearsals. Photo 223.jpg|[[Jacques Houdek]] at Kyiv ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]])\nFile:ESC2018 - Croatia 01.jpg|[[Franka Bateli\u0107|Franka]] at Lisbon ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]])\nFile:ESC2019-Croatia.jpg|[[Roko Bla\u017eevi\u0107|Roko]] at Tel Aviv ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Croatia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n*[[Dora Peja\u010devi\u0107]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090818124200/http://www.hrt.hr/dora/ \"Dora\" - Croatian ESC Pre-selection]\n*[https://eurosong.hr/povijest/povijest-dore/ Povijest Dore] {{in lang|hr}} ''eurosong.hr''\n\n{{Croatia in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Music of Croatia}}\n\n[[Category:Music festivals in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Croatia in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dummelaksen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eContestants", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Croatia_in_the_Eurovision_Song_Contest"}
{"title_page": "Kosala (novel)", "text_new": "{{italics title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Kosala\n| title_orig    = \u0915\u094b\u0938\u0932\u093e\n| translator    = Sudhakar Marathe\n| image         = Cocoon Bhalchandra Nemade.jpeg\n| caption       = Cover of English translation \n| author        = [[Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[India]]\n| language      = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| subject       = [[Existentialism]], [[Social alienation|alienation]]\n| genre         = \n| set_in        = 1950s [[Khandesh]] ([[Central India]]) and [[Pune]]\n| publisher     = Popular Publications<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\">{{cite book|first=Anjali|last=Nerlekar|title=Bombay Modern: Arun Kolatkar and Bilingual Literary Culture|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/45382|year=2016|publisher=Northwestern University Press|isbn=978-0-8101-3275-7|page=274|via=[[Project MUSE]]}}{{Subscription required}}</ref>\n| pub_date      = September 1963\n| english_pub_date = 1997\n| media_type    = \n| pages         = \n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = 38258018\n}}\n\n'''''Kosala''''' ({{lang-en|Cocoon}}), sometimes spelled '''''Kosla''''', is a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] novel by Indian writer [[Bhalchandra Nemade]], published in [[1963 in literature|1963]]. At the time of its publication, he was 25. Regarded as Nemade's [[magnum opus]], and accepted as a modern classic of [[Marathi literature]], the novel uses the [[Autobiographical novel|autobiographical form]] to narrate the journey of a young man, Pandurang Sangvikar, and his friends through his college years. Since its publication, the novel has been considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-ended nature and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been translated into eight Indian languages, and into English.\n\n==Publication==\n''Kosala'' is Bhalchandra Nemade's [[debut novel]], written over a two-week period in 1963 when he was twenty-five. It was published in September of the same year, and quickly became a success. Several editions appeared in the following years, and its twenty-second edition was published in 2013.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\">{{cite journal|last=Chitre|first=Dilip|author-link=Dilip Chitre|title=Alienation in Four Marathi Novels|year=1969|journal=Humanist Review|publisher=Modern Education Foundation|publication-place=Bombay|volume=1|issue=2|page=161\u2013175|oclc=1752400}}</ref><ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\">{{cite book|last=Gurjarpadhye-Khanderparkar|first=Prachi|title=Reinventing the Self: Nativist Cultural Imagination of \"Kosla\"|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=July\u2013August 2014|volume=58|issue=4|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=172\u2013185|jstor=44753804}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Contents==\n''Kosala'' uses the [[first-person narrative]] technique to recount the first twenty-five years in the life of Pandurang Sangavikar,<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> a young man of rural upbringing who moves to [[Pune]] for his higher education. He feels isolated in his new social setting, and this persistent feeling of estrangement leads him to return home. There, he encounters further disillusionment, with the death of his sister, his father's domination, and his own financial dependence.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\">{{cite book|author1=Nalini Natarajan|author2=Emmanuel Sampath Nelson|title=Handbook of Twentieth-century Literatures of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lTnv6o-d_oC&pg=PA233|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Westport|isbn=978-0-313-28778-7|page=233}}</ref> The novel aims to portray the spectrum of society from the viewpoint of Pandurang as a young boy.<ref name=\"Hatkanagalekar1980\">{{cite journal|last=Hatkanagalekar|first=M.D.|title=Marathi: A Desirable Advance|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=November-December 1980|volume=23|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|issue=6|page=146|jstor=23330269}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nMain characters:<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|title=Masterpieces of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dXFOAAAAYAAJ|volume=|year=1997|publisher=[[National Book Trust]]|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-237-1978-8|page=875\u2013877}}</ref>\n* '''Pandurang Sangavikar''': The protagonist, and only son of a rich village farmer. His fellow hostel students call him by his [[nickname]], Pandu.\n* '''Pandurang's father''': The head of a joint family, and a rich and respected man in his village.\n* '''Mani''': Pandurang's younger sister.\n* '''Giridhar''': Pandurang's village friend.\n* '''Suresh Bapat''': Pandurang's college friend in Pune.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story unfolds during the 1950s in [[Khandesh]] (a region in [[Central India]]), and in Pune.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/> Using the autobiographical form, ''Kosala'' narrates the life-story of Pandurang Sangvikar, a young man of 25, in six sections.  \n\nPandurang is the son of well-to-do farmer from Sangvi, a village in Khandesh. His family includes his parents, his grandmother, and his four sisters. Pandurang's relationship with his father is a difficult one, and they have been estranged since Pandurang was a boy. His father, who typifies the patriarchal family head, beats his son in childhood for wandering around in the company of friends. He does not allow the young boy to learn to play flute, or to perform in his school's plays. Pandurang considers his father excessively money-minded, materialistic, selfish, unscrupulous, and dictatorial. In sharp contrast to his relationship with his father, Pandurang loves his mother and his sisters dearly.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nAfter passing his local school's matriculation examination, Pandurang moves to [[Pune]] to attend college.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/> While studying, Pandurang lives in a hostel. He decides to make the most of college life, and becomes the secretary of the college debating society, prefect of the hostel, and directs a play at the college Annual Day function. Out of kindness, he gives responsibility for management of the hostel mess to one of his poorer friends. But, although Pandurang tries to help everyone around him, he ultimately discovers that his friends are using him. Finally, when he fails his exams badly and his financial position deteriorates, his father becomes angered by Pandurang's life-style. Pandurang learns a lesson: that good deeds do not count for much in life.<ref name=\"George1993\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|editor-link=K. M. George (writer)|title=Modern Indian Literature: an Anthology: Fiction|volume=Vol. 2|year=1993|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-7201-506-2|page=745}}</ref>\n\nIn his second year of college, Pandurang is an entirely new man, carefree and adventurous. Even his father now hesitates to ask him to mend his ways. He is shaken by the untimely death of his younger sister, Mani, but otherwise has no care for anything. In consequence, he fails his exam. After unsuccessful attempts to find work in the city, ultimately Pandurang returns to his village, his mind \"existentially vacant\". He is now one among many unemployed youngsters of the village. As Pandurang tries to understand their views on life, their sorrows and their joys, the true meaning of life begins to dawn.<ref name=\"George1993\"/>\n\n==Theme and techniques==\nThe main theme of ''Kosala'' is [[Social alienation|alienation]].<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel is influenced by [[existential philosophy]],<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> exploring existentialist ideas such as an obsession with birth and death, dread, alienation, and absurdity. Like other [[Existentialism#Literature|existential novels]], ''Kosala'' uses the [[First-person narrative|first person point of view]] to recount an individual's experiences, and in this exploration raises many questions regarding the [[meaning of life]] and the value of existence. It is considered the first existential novel in Marathi literature.<ref>{{cite thesis|first=Dattatraya Dnyandev|last=Khaladkar |title=Existentialism in the Selected American and Marathi Novels: a Comparative Study|chapter=Existentialism in Marathi Novels |chapter-url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/9899/7/07_chapter%203.pdf |year=2010 |publisher=Department of English, Shivaji University |location=Kolhapur|type=Ph.D|pages=144\u2013145|hdl=10603/9899}}</ref>\n\nThe novel's protagonist, Pandurang, has been described as a \"quintessential [[antihero|anti-hero]]\",<ref name=\"Padgaonkar1997\">{{cite journal|last=Padgaonkar|first=Latika|title=Cocoon by Bhalchandra Nemade (Book Review)|journal=The Book Review|volume=21|year=1997|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|location=New Delhi|page=42|oclc=564170386}}</ref> refusing all forms of colonial modernity: [[literacy]], [[Western culture|Western]] education, [[urbanisation]], [[industrialisation]], [[capitalism]], [[nationalism]], and the values of \"progress\" they embody.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/>\n\nPandurang is estranged from his father, right from his childhood. Later on in the novel, this estrangement develops into a major theme of mute revolt on the part of the younger generation, against the patriarchal system of values so characteristic of traditional Indian life. Pandurang has not so far found anything meaningful in his experience of village life. The same experience of meaninglessness repeats itself in his college life too in Pune, spread over six years.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe novel has been written in an epistolary fashion, where it reads like a number of diary entries. The language of the protagonist, Sangvikar, is an instrument in divulging his worldview. He uses a Marathi dialect spoken in rural Maharashtra. Despite the pessimistic undertones, there is an element of humour throughout the novel.  Another technique employed by the author is that the narration describes \"historical investigations\" often undertaken by Sangvikar and his friend Suresh Bapat, which ultimately uncover to them the absurdity and pathos of their conditions.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} It uses oblique, irrelevant humour as a serious moral strategy to unmask the phoneyness of society and culture.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe narrative of the novel fuses different types of genres such as the autobiography, the diary, the novel, the Indian folktales, folk narratives, and medieval saint literature. The language used in the novel are standard, archaic, urban, non-urban dialects, slangs, jargons, and sometimes poetic and rhetoric.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/> ''Kosala'' is said to have been inspired partially by [[J. D. Salinger]]'s ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''.<ref name=\"Sarang1992\">{{cite journal|last=Sarang|first=Vilas|title=Tradition and Conflict in the Context of Marathi Literature|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=September\u2013October 1992|volume=35|issue=5|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=159\u2013168|jstor=23337173}} {{closed access}}</ref> The narration style is similar as that of ''The Catcher in the Rye''.<ref name=\"Nandgaonkar 2015\">{{cite web|last=Nandgaonkar|first=Satish|title=Marathi Novelist Bhalchandra Nemade Chosen for Jnanpith Award|website=The Hindu|date=6 February 2015|url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/marathi-novelist-bhalchandra-nemade-chosen-for-jnanpith-award/article6865738.ece|access-date=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Kosala'' is widely regarded as a modern classic<ref name=\"DattaLal1991\">{{cite book|last=Lal|first=Mohan|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: Navaratri-Sarvasena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sOsbAAAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-260-1003-1|ignore-isbn-error=true|pages=27, 274}}</ref> and a path-breaking novel<ref name=\"Hindustan Times\">{{cite web | title=Jnanpith award for Marathi author Bhalchandra Nemade - india | website=Hindustan Times | date=7 February 2015| url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/jnanpith-award-for-marathi-author-bhalchandra-nemade/story-Q1mRTvFdbJOnX9DpuUfTeK.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> which left its mark on the ''sathottari'' (post-1960) Marathi fiction.<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\"/> With its publication, Nemade was considered a representative writer of his generation.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel received immediate critical acclaim after its publication and heralded a new trend in Marathi literature.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> Since its publication the novel is considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-endedness and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been the most appreciated and widely interpreted novel by critics including [[Dilip Chitre]], [[Narhar Ambadas Kurundkar|Narhar Kurundkar]], Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar, [[Vilas Sarang]], Sukanya Aagase, Rekha Inamdar-Sane and  Vasudev Sawant. Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar wrote that, \"It was only ''Kosla'', which responding as it did to a crisis in the cultural consciousness of [[Maharashtra]], that opened up new, native possibilities of form and meaning and thus sought to change the direction of both literary taste and fictional tradition\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Digole|first=D. P.|title=Bhalchandra Nemade's Kosla: A Narrative of Revolt and Trapped Anguish|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=78295873&site=lrc-plus|journal=Labyrinth: An International Refereed Journal of Postmodern Studies|date=July 2012|volume=3|issue=3|pages=21\u201329|issn=0976-0814|via=[[EBSCO Information Services|Literary Reference Center Plus]]}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n''Kosala'' has been adapted into a play, ''Me, Pandurang Sangavikar'' ({{abbr|lit.|literally}} I am Pandurang Sangavikar), directed by Mandar Deshpande.<ref name=\"Banerjee 2016\">{{cite web | last=Banerjee | first=Kaushani | title=Pratibimb Marathi Natya Utsav: A mix of commercial and experimental plays - art and culture | website=Hindustan Times | date=31 July 2016 | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/pratibimb-marathi-natya-utsav-a-mix-of-commercial-and-experimental-plays/story-U4aGM5aNQhQvt5FxqRJR3L.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n''Kosala'' has been translated into eight Indian languages and also into English. The available translations of the novel are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Title !! Languge !! Translator !! Year !! Publisher !! Ref.\n|-\n| ''Cocoon'' || English  || Sudhakar Marathe || 1997 || Macmillan Publishers India, Chennai ||<ref>{{cite book|title=The Book Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KyHhAAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|page=31}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Hindi]] || - || 1983 || [[National Book Trust]], [[New Delhi]] ||\n|-\n| ''Kosheto'' || [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] || Usha Sheth || 1995  || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Kannada]] || Vaman Dattatraya Bendre || 1995 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||<ref name=\"Dutt1999\">{{cite book|author=Kartik Chandra Dutt|title=Who's who of Indian Writers, 1999: A-M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QA1V7sICaIwC&pg=PA127|year=1999|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-0873-5|page=127}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Palur Vah'' || [[Assamese language|Assamese]] || - || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] || Ajit Singh || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Need'' || [[Bengali language|Bengali]] || Vandana Alase Hazra || 2001 || [[Sahitya Akademi]], [[New Delhi]] ||<ref name=\"Rao2004\">{{cite book|last=Rao|first=D. S.|title=Five Decades: The National Academy of Letters, India : a Short History of Sahitya Akademi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8JDsBBDoMccC&pg=PA11|year=2004|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-2060-7|page=11}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Urdu]] || - || 2002 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Koshapok'' || [[Odia language|Odia]] || - || 2005 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Google books|id=ywj6VehHd5oC}} (Marathi)\n* {{Google books|id=ue41AAAAMAAJ}} (Hindi translation)\n\n[[Category:1963 novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n[[Category:Marathi novels]]\n[[Category:Existentialist novels]]\n[[Category:1963 Indian novels]]\n[[Category:1963 debut novels]]\n[[Category:Indian autobiographical novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{italics title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Kosala\n| title_orig    = \u0915\u094b\u0938\u0932\u093e\n| translator    = Sudhakar Marathe\n| image         = Cocoon Bhalchandra Nemade.jpeg\n| caption       = Cover of English translation \n| author        = [[Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[India]]\n| language      = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| subject       = [[Existentialism]], [[Social alienation|alienation]]\n| genre         = \n| set_in        = 1950s [[Khandesh]] ([[Central India]]) and [[Pune]]\n| publisher     = Popular Publications<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\">{{cite book|first=Anjali|last=Nerlekar|title=Bombay Modern: Arun Kolatkar and Bilingual Literary Culture|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/45382|year=2016|publisher=Northwestern University Press|isbn=978-0-8101-3275-7|page=274|via=[[Project MUSE]]}}{{Subscription required}}</ref>\n| pub_date      = September 1963\n| english_pub_date = 1997\n| media_type    = \n| pages         = \n| isbn          = \n| oclc          = 38258018\n}}\n\n'''''Kosala''''' ({{lang-en|Cocoon}}), sometimes spelled '''''Kosla''''', is a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] novel by Indian writer [[Bhalchandra Nemade]], published in [[1963 in literature|1963]]. At the time of its publication, he was 25. Regarded as Nemade's [[magnum opus]], and accepted as a modern classic of [[Marathi literature]], the novel uses the [[Autobiographical novel|autobiographical form]] to narrate the journey of a young man, Pandurang Sangvikar, and his friends through his college years. Since its publication, the novel has been considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-ended nature and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been translated into eight Indian languages, and into English.\n\n==Publication==\n''Kosala'' is Bhalchandra Nemade's [[debut novel]], written over a two-week period in 1963 when he was twenty-five. It was published in September of the same year, and quickly became a success. Several editions appeared in the following years, and its twenty-second edition was published in 2013.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\">{{cite journal|last=Chitre|first=Dilip|author-link=Dilip Chitre|title=Alienation in Four Marathi Novels|year=1969|journal=Humanist Review|publisher=Modern Education Foundation|publication-place=Bombay|volume=1|issue=2|page=161\u2013175|oclc=1752400}}</ref><ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\">{{cite book|last=Gurjarpadhye-Khanderparkar|first=Prachi|title=Reinventing the Self: Nativist Cultural Imagination of \"Kosla\"|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=July\u2013August 2014|volume=58|issue=4|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=172\u2013185|jstor=44753804}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Contents==\n''Kosala'' uses the [[first-person narrative]] technique to recount the first twenty-five years in the life of Pandurang Sangavikar,<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> a young man of rural upbringing who moves to [[Pune]] for his higher education. He feels isolated in his new social setting, and this persistent feeling of estrangement leads him to return home. There, he encounters further disillusionment, with the death of his sister, his father's domination, and his own financial dependence.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\">{{cite book|author1=Nalini Natarajan|author2=Emmanuel Sampath Nelson|title=Handbook of Twentieth-century Literatures of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lTnv6o-d_oC&pg=PA233|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|location=Westport|isbn=978-0-313-28778-7|page=233}}</ref> The novel aims to portray the spectrum of society from the viewpoint of Pandurang as a young boy.<ref name=\"Hatkanagalekar1980\">{{cite journal|last=Hatkanagalekar|first=M.D.|title=Marathi: A Desirable Advance|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=November-December 1980|volume=23|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|issue=6|page=146|jstor=23330269}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nMain characters:<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|title=Masterpieces of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dXFOAAAAYAAJ|volume=|year=1997|publisher=[[National Book Trust]]|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-237-1978-8|page=875\u2013877}}</ref>\n* '''Pandurang Sangavikar''': The protagonist, and only son of a rich village farmer. His fellow hostel students call him by his [[nickname]], Pandu.\n* '''Pandurang's father''': The head of a joint family, and a rich and respected man in his village.\n* '''Mani''': Pandurang's younger sister.\n* '''Giridhar''': Pandurang's village friend.\n* '''Suresh Bapat''': Pandurang's college friend in Pune.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story unfolds during the 1950s in [[Khandesh]] (a region in [[Central India]]), and in Pune.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/> Using the autobiographical form, the novel narrates the life-story of Pandurang Sangvikar, a young man of 25, in six sections.  \n\nPandurang is the son of well-to-do farmer from Sangvi, a village in Khandesh. His family includes his parents, his grandmother, and his four sisters. Pandurang's relationship with his father is a difficult one, and they have been estranged since Pandurang was a boy. His father, who typifies the patriarchal family head, beats his son in childhood for wandering around in the company of friends. He does not allow the young boy to learn to play flute, or to perform in his school's plays. Pandurang considers his father excessively money-minded, materialistic, selfish, unscrupulous, and dictatorial. In sharp contrast to his relationship with his father, Pandurang loves his mother and his sisters dearly.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nAfter passing his local school's matriculation examination, Pandurang moves to [[Pune]] to attend college.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/> While studying, Pandurang lives in a hostel. He decides to make the most of college life, and becomes the secretary of the college debating society, prefect of the hostel, and directs a play at the college Annual Day function. Out of kindness, he gives responsibility for management of the hostel mess to one of his poorer friends. But, although Pandurang tries to help everyone around him, he ultimately discovers that his friends are using him. Finally, when he fails his exams badly and his financial position deteriorates, his father becomes angered by Pandurang's life-style. Pandurang learns a lesson: that good deeds do not count for much in life.<ref name=\"George1993\">{{cite book|editor-last=George|editor-first=K. M.|editor-link=K. M. George (writer)|title=Modern Indian Literature: an Anthology: Fiction|volume=Vol. 2|year=1993|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-7201-506-2|page=745}}</ref>\n\nIn his second year of college, Pandurang is an entirely new man, carefree and adventurous. Even his father now hesitates to ask him to mend his ways. He is shaken by the untimely death of his younger sister, Mani, but otherwise has no care for anything. In consequence, he fails his exam. After unsuccessful attempts to find work in the city, ultimately Pandurang returns to his village, his mind \"existentially vacant\". He is now one among many unemployed youngsters of the village. As Pandurang tries to understand their views on life, their sorrows and their joys, the true meaning of life begins to dawn.<ref name=\"George1993\"/>\n\n==Theme and techniques==\nThe main theme of ''Kosala'' is [[Social alienation|alienation]].<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel is influenced by [[existential philosophy]],<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> exploring existentialist ideas such as an obsession with birth and death, dread, alienation, and absurdity. Like other [[Existentialism#Literature|existential novels]], ''Kosala'' uses the [[First-person narrative|first person point of view]] to recount an individual's experiences, and in this exploration raises many questions regarding the [[meaning of life]] and the value of existence. It is considered the first existential novel in Marathi literature.<ref>{{cite thesis|first=Dattatraya Dnyandev|last=Khaladkar |title=Existentialism in the Selected American and Marathi Novels: a Comparative Study|chapter=Existentialism in Marathi Novels |chapter-url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/9899/7/07_chapter%203.pdf |year=2010 |publisher=Department of English, Shivaji University |location=Kolhapur|type=Ph.D|pages=144\u2013145|hdl=10603/9899}}</ref>\n\nThe novel's protagonist, Pandurang, has been described as a \"quintessential [[antihero|anti-hero]]\",<ref name=\"Padgaonkar1997\">{{cite journal|last=Padgaonkar|first=Latika|title=Cocoon by Bhalchandra Nemade (Book Review)|journal=The Book Review|volume=21|year=1997|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|location=New Delhi|page=42|oclc=564170386}}</ref> refusing all forms of colonial modernity: [[literacy]], [[Western culture|Western]] education, [[urbanisation]], [[industrialisation]], [[capitalism]], [[nationalism]], and the values of \"progress\" they embody.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/>\n\nPandurang is estranged from his father, right from his childhood. Later on in the novel, this estrangement develops into a major theme of mute revolt on the part of the younger generation, against the patriarchal system of values so characteristic of traditional Indian life. Pandurang has not so far found anything meaningful in his experience of village life. The same experience of meaninglessness repeats itself in his college life too in Pune, spread over six years.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe novel has been written in an epistolary fashion, where it reads like a number of diary entries. The language of the protagonist, Sangvikar, is an instrument in divulging his worldview. He uses a Marathi dialect spoken in rural Maharashtra. Despite the pessimistic undertones, there is an element of humour throughout the novel.  Another technique employed by the author is that the narration describes \"historical investigations\" often undertaken by Sangvikar and his friend Suresh Bapat, which ultimately uncover to them the absurdity and pathos of their conditions.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}} It uses oblique, irrelevant humour as a serious moral strategy to unmask the phoneyness of society and culture.<ref name=\"KMGeorge1997\"/>\n\nThe narrative of the novel fuses different types of genres such as the autobiography, the diary, the novel, the Indian folktales, folk narratives, and medieval saint literature. The language used in the novel are standard, archaic, urban, non-urban dialects, slangs, jargons, and sometimes poetic and rhetoric.<ref name=\"Gurjarpadhye2014\"/> ''Kosala'' is said to have been inspired partially by [[J. D. Salinger]]'s ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]''.<ref name=\"Sarang1992\">{{cite journal|last=Sarang|first=Vilas|title=Tradition and Conflict in the Context of Marathi Literature|journal=[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]|date=September\u2013October 1992|volume=35|issue=5|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|pages=159\u2013168|jstor=23337173}} {{closed access}}</ref> The narration style is similar as that of ''The Catcher in the Rye''.<ref name=\"Nandgaonkar 2015\">{{cite web|last=Nandgaonkar|first=Satish|title=Marathi Novelist Bhalchandra Nemade Chosen for Jnanpith Award|website=The Hindu|date=6 February 2015|url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/books-authors/marathi-novelist-bhalchandra-nemade-chosen-for-jnanpith-award/article6865738.ece|access-date=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Kosala'' is widely regarded as a modern classic<ref name=\"DattaLal1991\">{{cite book|last=Lal|first=Mohan|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: Navaratri-Sarvasena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sOsbAAAAIAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-260-1003-1|ignore-isbn-error=true|pages=27, 274}}</ref> and a path-breaking novel<ref name=\"Hindustan Times\">{{cite web | title=Jnanpith award for Marathi author Bhalchandra Nemade - india | website=Hindustan Times | date=7 February 2015| url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/jnanpith-award-for-marathi-author-bhalchandra-nemade/story-Q1mRTvFdbJOnX9DpuUfTeK.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref> which left its mark on the ''sathottari'' (post-1960) Marathi fiction.<ref name=\"Nerlekar2016\"/> With its publication, Nemade was considered a representative writer of his generation.<ref name=\"Chitre1969\"/> The novel received immediate critical acclaim after its publication and heralded a new trend in Marathi literature.<ref name=\"NatarajanNelson1996\"/> Since its publication the novel is considered a trendsetter in Marathi literature due to its open-endedness and its potential for varied interpretation. It has been the most appreciated and widely interpreted novel by critics including [[Dilip Chitre]], [[Narhar Ambadas Kurundkar|Narhar Kurundkar]], Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar, [[Vilas Sarang]], Sukanya Aagase, Rekha Inamdar-Sane and  Vasudev Sawant. Chandrashekhar Jahagirdar wrote that, \"It was only ''Kosla'', which responding as it did to a crisis in the cultural consciousness of [[Maharashtra]], that opened up new, native possibilities of form and meaning and thus sought to change the direction of both literary taste and fictional tradition\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Digole|first=D. P.|title=Bhalchandra Nemade's Kosla: A Narrative of Revolt and Trapped Anguish|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lkh&AN=78295873&site=lrc-plus|journal=Labyrinth: An International Refereed Journal of Postmodern Studies|date=July 2012|volume=3|issue=3|pages=21\u201329|issn=0976-0814|via=[[EBSCO Information Services|Literary Reference Center Plus]]}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\n''Kosala'' has been adapted into a play, ''Me, Pandurang Sangavikar'' ({{abbr|lit.|literally}} I am Pandurang Sangavikar), directed by Mandar Deshpande.<ref name=\"Banerjee 2016\">{{cite web | last=Banerjee | first=Kaushani | title=Pratibimb Marathi Natya Utsav: A mix of commercial and experimental plays - art and culture | website=Hindustan Times | date=31 July 2016 | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/pratibimb-marathi-natya-utsav-a-mix-of-commercial-and-experimental-plays/story-U4aGM5aNQhQvt5FxqRJR3L.html | access-date=8 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n''Kosala'' has been translated into eight Indian languages and also into English. The available translations of the novel are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Title !! Languge !! Translator !! Year !! Publisher !! Ref.\n|-\n| ''Cocoon'' || English  || Sudhakar Marathe || 1997 || Macmillan Publishers India, Chennai ||<ref>{{cite book|title=The Book Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KyHhAAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=C. Chari for Perspective Publications|page=31}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Hindi]] || - || 1983 || [[National Book Trust]], [[New Delhi]] ||\n|-\n| ''Kosheto'' || [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] || Usha Sheth || 1995  || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Kannada]] || Vaman Dattatraya Bendre || 1995 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||<ref name=\"Dutt1999\">{{cite book|author=Kartik Chandra Dutt|title=Who's who of Indian Writers, 1999: A-M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QA1V7sICaIwC&pg=PA127|year=1999|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-0873-5|page=127}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Palur Vah'' || [[Assamese language|Assamese]] || - || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] || Ajit Singh || 1996 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Need'' || [[Bengali language|Bengali]] || Vandana Alase Hazra || 2001 || [[Sahitya Akademi]], [[New Delhi]] ||<ref name=\"Rao2004\">{{cite book|last=Rao|first=D. S.|title=Five Decades: The National Academy of Letters, India : a Short History of Sahitya Akademi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8JDsBBDoMccC&pg=PA11|year=2004|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-2060-7|page=11}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kosala'' || [[Urdu]] || - || 2002 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|-\n| ''Koshapok'' || [[Odia language|Odia]] || - || 2005 || National Book Trust, New Delhi ||\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Google books|id=ywj6VehHd5oC}} (Marathi)\n* {{Google books|id=ue41AAAAMAAJ}} (Hindi translation)\n\n[[Category:1963 novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Bhalchandra Nemade]]\n[[Category:Marathi novels]]\n[[Category:Existentialist novels]]\n[[Category:1963 Indian novels]]\n[[Category:1963 debut novels]]\n[[Category:Indian autobiographical novels]]\n", "name_user": "FiveFaintFootprints", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:ce - expression tweak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosala_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Makoti Khawula", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Makoti Khawula\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image               = Makoti Khawula sworn in.png\n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Khawula at her swearing-in in May 2019\n| office              = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| status              = \n| term_start          = 21 May 2014\n| term_end            = \n| constituency        = [[KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| birthname           = Makoti Sibongile Khawula<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula - Parliament of South Africa |url=https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/108 |website=parliament.gov.za |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1954|12|07|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty          = [[African National Congress]] {{small|(1980\u20132013)}}\n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Durban University of Technology]]\n| occupation          = Member of Parliament\n| profession          = Politician\n| known_for           = Her refusal to speak [[English language|English]] in Parliament\n| committees          = Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth and Persons with Disabilities (Alternate Member)\n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Makoti Sibongile Khawula''' (born 7 December 1954) is a [[Zulu people|Zulu]] South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist from [[KwaZulu-Natal]] serving  as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] for the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) since 2014. Khawula is known for her refusal to speak English in Parliament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zulu |first1=Makhosandile |title=EFF MP maKhawula calls Mabuza a liar |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2002728/eff-mp-makhawula-calls-mabuza-a-liar/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=30 August 2018|quote=Khawula is known for speaking IsiZulu in parliament and on social media platforms has gained popularity for providing a degree of entertainment during sessions in the house.}}</ref>\n==Early life and education==\nKhawula was born on 7 December 1954 in [[Durban]] in the former [[Natal Province]]. She only fulfilled grade 8 while attending school. She later completed a certficate in surveying from the [[Durban University of Technology]] and a Doctors For Life course in Home Based Care.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n==Political career==\n===Political activism===\nKhawula joined the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) and participated in anti-apartheid activities in the Durban communities of [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal|Inanda]] and [[KwaMashu]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"pa\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula (EFF) - Interview |url=https://www.pa.org.za/blog/ms-makoti-sibongile-khawula-eff |website=People's Assembly |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> She became an organiser for the ANC in 1990. Within the ANC, she was a member of the party's [[African National Congress Women's League|Women's League]], a provincial election organiser in 1994 and a development activist for the party. She became a member of the party's Regional Executive Committee in 2013. She was also the chairperson of both the [[South African Communist Party]] (SACP) and [[South African National Civic Organisation]] (SANCO) in ward 54 of the [[eThekwini Metropolitan Municipality]].<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" /> She left the ANC in 2013 and joined the newly-formed EFF in the same year.<ref name=\"pa\" />\n===Parliamentary career===\nKhawula became a Member of Parliament on 21 May 2014 following the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general elections]]. She was assigned to serve on the Portfolio Committee on Water and Sanitation and the Prtfolio Committee on Women in the Presidency.<ref name=\"news24\">{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=Meet the EFF MP who refuses to speak English in Parliament |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/meet-the-eff-mp-who-refuses-to-speak-english-in-parliament-20151222 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 December 2015 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nShe soon became known for her refusal to speak English while speaking in Parliament. She either speaks [[Zulu people|isiZulu]] or [[Xhosa language|isiXhosa]] when delivering speeches or asking oratory questions. She insists that she will speak the language of her constituency.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\nShe was re-elected to a second term in the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general elections]]. She now serves as an Alternate Member of the  Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth, Children and People with Disability.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n==Personal life==\nIn the Register of Members' Interests for 2014, Khawula declared that she received social grants for two foster children.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Rebecca |title=MPs\u2019 financial interests revealed: Some cats are fatter than others |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-09-19-mps-financial-interests-revealed-some-cats-are-fatter-than-others/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=19 September 2014}}</ref> These were not part of the 2015 register.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/makoti-sibongile-khawula/ Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula \u2013 People's Assembly]\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khawula, Makoti}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Zulu people]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kwa-Zulu Natal]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Makoti Khawula\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image               = Makoti Khawula sworn in.png\n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Khawula at her swearing-in in May 2019\n| office              = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| status              = \n| term_start          = 21 May 2014\n| term_end            = \n| constituency        = [[KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| birthname           = Makoti Sibongile Khawula<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula - Parliament of South Africa |url=https://www.parliament.gov.za/person-details/108 |website=parliament.gov.za |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1954|12|07|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty          = [[African National Congress]] {{small|(1980\u20132013)}}\n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Durban University of Technology]]\n| occupation          = Member of Parliament\n| profession          = Politician\n| known_for           = Her refusal to speak [[English language|English]] in Parliament\n| committees          = Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth and Persons with Disabilities (Alternate Member)\n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Makoti Sibongile Khawula''' (born 7 December 1954) is a [[Zulu people|Zulu]] South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist from [[KwaZulu-Natal]] serving  as a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] for the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] (EFF) since 2014. Khawula is known for her refusal to speak English in Parliament.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zulu |first1=Makhosandile |title=EFF MP maKhawula calls Mabuza a liar |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2002728/eff-mp-makhawula-calls-mabuza-a-liar/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=30 August 2018|quote=Khawula is known for speaking IsiZulu in parliament and on social media platforms has gained popularity for providing a degree of entertainment during sessions in the house.}}</ref>\n==Early life and education==\nKhawula was born on 7 December 1954 in [[Durban]] in the former [[Natal Province]]. She only fulfilled grade 8 while attending school. She later completed a certficate in surveying from the [[Durban University of Technology]] and a Doctors For Life course in Home Based Care.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n==Political career==\n===Political activism===\nKhawula joined the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) and participated in anti-apartheid activities in the Durban communities of [[Inanda, KwaZulu-Natal|Inanda]] and [[KwaMashu]] in the 1980s.<ref name=\"pa\">{{cite web |title=Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula (EFF) - Interview |url=https://www.pa.org.za/blog/ms-makoti-sibongile-khawula-eff |website=People's Assembly |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> She became an organiser for the ANC in 1990. Within the ANC, she was a member of the party's [[African National Congress Women's League|Women's League]], a provincial election organiser in 1994 and a development activist for the party. She became a member of the party's Regional Executive Committee in 2013. She was also the chairperson of both the [[South African Communist Party]] (SACP) and [[South African National Civic Organisation]] (SANCO) in ward 54 of the [[eThekwini Metropolitan Municipality]].<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" /> She left the ANC in 2013 and joined the newly-formed EFF in the same year.<ref name=\"pa\" />\n===Parliamentary career===\nKhawula became a Member of Parliament on 21 May 2014 following the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general elections]]. She was assigned to serve on the Portfolio Committee on Water and Sanitation and the Prtfolio Committee on Women in the Presidency.<ref name=\"news24\">{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=Meet the EFF MP who refuses to speak English in Parliament |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/meet-the-eff-mp-who-refuses-to-speak-english-in-parliament-20151222 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 December 2015 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nShe soon became known for her refusal to speak English while speaking in Parliament. She either speaks [[Zulu people|isiZulu]] or [[Xhosa language|isiXhosa]] when delivering speeches or asking oratory questions. She insists that she will speak the language of her constituency.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\nShe was re-elected to a second term in the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general elections]]. She now serves as an Alternate Member of the  Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth, Children and People with Disability.<ref name=\"parliamentgovza\" />\n==Personal life==\nIn the Register of Members' Interests for 2014, Khawula declared that she received social grants for two foster children.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Rebecca |title=MPs\u2019 financial interests revealed: Some cats are fatter than others |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-09-19-mps-financial-interests-revealed-some-cats-are-fatter-than-others/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=19 September 2014}}</ref> These were not part of the 2015 register.<ref name=\"news24\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/makoti-sibongile-khawula/ Ms Makoti Sibongile Khawula \u2013 People's Assembly]\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khawula, Makoti}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Zulu people]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kwa-Zulu Natal]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added residence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Makoti_Khawula"}
{"title_page": "Sounding the Seventh Trumpet", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Sounding the Seventh Trumpet\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Avenged Sevenfold]]\n| cover      = Ststoriginal.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 24, 2001<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/>\n| recorded   = November 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avengedsevenfold.com|title=Official A7X Homepage|date=March 1, 2001|accessdate=October 29, 2013| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20010306001342/http://www.avenged7fold.com/main.htm#news| archivedate=March 6, 2001 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Westbeach Recorders]]\n| genre      = [[Metalcore]]\n| length     = 53:12\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Good Life Recordings|Good Life]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r543419/review|pure_url=yes}}|title=Sounding the Seventh Trumpet - Avenged Sevenfold|publisher=[[Allmusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegels.tv/music/album-getinfo/sounding-the-seventh-trumpet/80e6be11-86f5-4d0b-9d55-0f1c62b7afb8.cfm |title=\"Sounding The Seventh Trumpet\" by Avenged Sevenfold |publisher=spiegels.tv |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>|[[Hopeless Records|Hopeless]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/sounding-the-seventh-trumpet-mr0000832060 |title=Sounding the Seventh Trumpet - Avenged Sevenfold &#124; Release Information, Reviews and Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2002-03-19 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Donnell Cameron]]|Avenged Sevenfold}}\n| prev_title = Demo\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[Waking the Fallen]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Sounding the Seventh Trumpet\n | type        = Album\n | single1     = [[Warmness on the Soul]]\n | single1date = April 10, 2001\n}}\n}}\n'''''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet''''' (also known as ''STST'' and ''ST7T'') is the debut studio album by American [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Avenged Sevenfold]], released in July 2001 and re-released on March 19, 2002,<ref name=\"cduniversexx\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/3007011/a/Sounding+The+Seventh+Trumpet.htm |title=Avenged Sevenfold - Sounding The Seventh Trumpet CD Album |publisher=Cduniverse.com |date=2002-03-19 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref> featuring slightly different cover art. Although the album only sold 300 copies in its first week of release, it has sold 370,000 copies worldwide with 310,000 sold in [[United States]], as of November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avenged-sevenfold-america.webs.com/a7xhist.html |title=A7X History |publisher=Avenged-sevenfold-america.webs.com |accessdate=2014-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054458/http://www.avenged-sevenfold-america.webs.com/a7xhist.html |archivedate=2013-09-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ivanzjnonkz.multiply.com/reviews |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195413/http://ivanzjnonkz.multiply.com/reviews |archivedate=2016-03-03 }} </ref> The title 'Sounding the Seventh Trumpet' takes its name from the [[Book of Revelation]], specifically referencing chapter 11 and the sounding of the last (seventh) trumpet, showing the end of the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bible.cc/revelation/11-15.htm |title=Revelation 11:15 The seventh angel sounded his trumpet, and there were loud voices in heaven, which said: \"The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Messiah, and he will reign for ever and ever.\" |publisher=Bible.cc |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref> Valary DiBenedetto ([[M. Shadows]]' future wife) performs vocals on the track \"The Art of Subconscious Illusion.\"<ref name=\"cduniversexx\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funtrivia.com/en/Music/Avenged-Sevenfold-14579.html |title=Avenged Sevenfold - Fun Facts and Information |publisher=Funtrivia.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebriton.com/valary-dibenedetto |title=Valary DiBenedetto - Biography, Photos, Videos |publisher=Celebriton.Com |date=1982-04-07 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref> The album was released on [[gramophone record|vinyl]] for the first time in 2008 in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Avenged-Sevenfold-Sounding-The-Seventh-Trumpet/release/2604040|title=Sounding the Seventh Trumpet LP|publisher=Discogs.com|accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' was recorded in November 2000, with a budget of $2,000. When the band members got into the studio, The Rev recorded all the drums in one take, and the other members of the band added their parts to what he had laid down. Zacky Vengeance played lead guitar originally. Then, when Synyster Gates joined the band in early 2001, they recorded a heavy metal version of \"To End the Rapture\" with Gates playing lead guitar. This heavy metal version was first seen on the \"[[Warmness on the Soul]]\" single, and was later featured on the re-release of ''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet''. This is the only album to feature bassist Justin Sane, whom is also credited as playing piano on the original releases. He was briefly replaced by Dameon Ash as a touring bassist after the touring cycle, whom was then replaced by [[Johnny Christ]].\n\n==Release==\nThe release date of this album is theorized in many sources. On the band's official website, it's given as January 31, 2001. However, on archived versions of the website, news updates explain that the album, distributed by Lumberjack Distributions, was originally planned for a late April 2001 release. Due to unknown reasons, it had to be pushed back multiple times, at first for a June 10, then for a June 20 release. A [[Loudwire]] article about the album's 17th anniversary gives July 24 as the actual release date.<ref name=\"Loudwire\">{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/avenged-sevenfold-sounding-the-seventh-trumpet-album-anniversary/ |title=17 Years Ago: Avenged Sevenfold Introduce Themselves With \u2018Sounding the Seventh Trumpet\u2019 |publisher=Loudwire.com |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2018-11-27 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n|rev2 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref>''[[Kerrang!]]'' issue 880 (November 24, 2001).</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Ultimate Guitar]]''\n|rev3score=8.5/10<ref>{{cite web |title=Avenged Sevenfold: Sounding The Seventh Trumpet {{!}} Reviews @ Ultimate-Guitar.com |url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/reviews/compact_discs/avenged_sevenfold/sounding_the_seventh_trumpet/ |website=[[Ultimate Guitar]] |accessdate=3 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n}}\n''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' was generally well received by critics. [[Allmusic]] rated the album three stars out of five and wrote: \"''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' is a magnificent album that is suitable for any fan of [[heavy metal music|metal music]], as Avenged Sevenfold has a firm grasp on all that is extreme.\" The review also praised the tracks \"Darkness Surrounding\" and \"We Come out at Night\" as being \"...excellent [[metalcore]] masterpieces, as the vocal harmonies add to these cuts to evolve the songs into fully atmospheric sonic blasts.\"\n\n==Videography==\nAvenged Sevenfold later released the ''Warmness on the Soul'', which featured a video for the single \"Warmness on the Soul\". The video depicted the band wandering through city streets as M. Shadows' wife, Valary, searched for them. There is a [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] version of \"To End the Rapture\" which was released on the reissue of ''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' after it was bought by Hopeless Records.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xfi09_avenged-sevenfold-warmness-on-the-s_news |title=Avenged Sevenfold - Warmness On The Soul - Vid\u00e9o Dailymotion |publisher=Dailymotion.com |date=2006-09-25 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = Avenged Sevenfold, except where noted\n| title1          = To End the Rapture\n| length1         = 1:24\n| title2          = Turn the Other Way\n| length2         = 5:40\n| title3          = [[Darkness Surrounding]]\n| length3         = 4:53\n| title4          = The Art of Subconscious Illusion\n| note4           = featuring Valary DiBenedetto\n| length4         = 3:45\n| title5          = We Come Out at Night\n| length5         = 4:46\n| title6          = Lips of Deceit\n| length6         = 4:09\n| title7          = [[Warmness on the Soul]]\n| length7         = 4:19\n| title8          = An Epic of Time Wasted\n| length8         = 4:18\n| title9          = Breaking Their Hold\n| length9         = 1:11\n| title10         = Forgotten Faces\n| length10        = 3:26\n| title11         = Thick and Thin\n| length11        = 4:15\n| title12         = Streets\n| note12          = written by M. Shadows & Successful Failure\n| length12        = 3:06\n| title13         = Shattered by Broken Dreams\n| length13        = 7:12\n| total_length    = 53:11\n| title_width     = 740px\n}}\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The \"Heavy Metal Version\" of \"To End the Rapture\" was featured on the re-release of ''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'', replacing the original.\n\n==Personnel==\n;Avenged Sevenfold\n* [[M. Shadows]] \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar, keyboards\n* [[Zacky Vengeance]] \u2013 lead guitar\n* [[The Rev]] \u2013 drums, backing vocals, sound effects, additional vocals on \"The Art of Subconscious Illusion\"\n* Justin Sane \u2013 bass\n\n;Session musicians \n* Valary Di Benedetto \u2013 additional vocals on \"The Art of Subconscious Illusion\"\n* [[Synyster Gates]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals (only on \"To End the Rapture\")\n\n;Production\n* Recorded at Westbeach in [[Hollywood, California]], USA\n* Produced, engineered, and mixed by Donnell Cameron and Avenged Sevenfold\n* Assistant engineering by Henrah Kruzchev\n* Mastered by Ramon Breton and Avenged Sevenfold at Oceanview Mastering\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Avenged Sevenfold}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sounding The Seventh Trumpet}}\n[[Category:Avenged Sevenfold albums]]\n[[Category:2001 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Hopeless Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Sounding the Seventh Trumpet\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Avenged Sevenfold]]\n| cover      = Ststoriginal.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 24, 2001<ref name=\"Loudwire\"/>\n| recorded   = November 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avengedsevenfold.com|title=Official A7X Homepage|date=March 1, 2001|accessdate=October 29, 2013| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20010306001342/http://www.avenged7fold.com/main.htm#news| archivedate=March 6, 2001 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Westbeach Recorders]]\n| genre      = [[Metalcore]]\n| length     = 53:12\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Good Life Recordings|Good Life]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r543419/review|pure_url=yes}}|title=Sounding the Seventh Trumpet - Avenged Sevenfold|publisher=[[Allmusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegels.tv/music/album-getinfo/sounding-the-seventh-trumpet/80e6be11-86f5-4d0b-9d55-0f1c62b7afb8.cfm |title=\"Sounding The Seventh Trumpet\" by Avenged Sevenfold |publisher=spiegels.tv |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15 }}{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>|[[Hopeless Records|Hopeless]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/sounding-the-seventh-trumpet-mr0000832060 |title=Sounding the Seventh Trumpet - Avenged Sevenfold &#124; Release Information, Reviews and Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date=2002-03-19 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Donnell Cameron]]|Avenged Sevenfold}}\n| prev_title = Demo\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[Waking the Fallen]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Sounding the Seventh Trumpet\n | type        = Album\n | single1     = [[Warmness on the Soul]]\n | single1date = April 10, 2001\n}}\n}}\n'''''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet''''' (also known as ''STST'' and ''ST7T'') is the debut studio album by American [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Avenged Sevenfold]], released in July 2001 and re-released on March 19, 2002,<ref name=\"cduniversexx\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/3007011/a/Sounding+The+Seventh+Trumpet.htm |title=Avenged Sevenfold - Sounding The Seventh Trumpet CD Album |publisher=Cduniverse.com |date=2002-03-19 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref> featuring slightly different cover art. Although the album only sold 300 copies in its first week of release, it has sold 370,000 copies worldwide with 310,000 sold in [[United States]], as of November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avenged-sevenfold-america.webs.com/a7xhist.html |title=A7X History |publisher=Avenged-sevenfold-america.webs.com |accessdate=2014-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054458/http://www.avenged-sevenfold-america.webs.com/a7xhist.html |archivedate=2013-09-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ivanzjnonkz.multiply.com/reviews |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195413/http://ivanzjnonkz.multiply.com/reviews |archivedate=2016-03-03 }} </ref> The title 'Sounding the Seventh Trumpet' takes its name from the [[Book of Revelation]], specifically referencing chapter 11 and the sounding of the last (seventh) trumpet, showing the end of the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bible.cc/revelation/11-15.htm |title=Revelation 11:15 The seventh angel sounded his trumpet, and there were loud voices in heaven, which said: \"The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Messiah, and he will reign for ever and ever.\" |publisher=Bible.cc |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref> Valary DiBenedetto ([[M. Shadows]]' future wife) performs vocals on the track \"The Art of Subconscious Illusion.\"<ref name=\"cduniversexx\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funtrivia.com/en/Music/Avenged-Sevenfold-14579.html |title=Avenged Sevenfold - Fun Facts and Information |publisher=Funtrivia.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebriton.com/valary-dibenedetto |title=Valary DiBenedetto - Biography, Photos, Videos |publisher=Celebriton.Com |date=1982-04-07 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref> The album was released as [[gramophone record|2x12 vinyl]], [[LP album|LP]], 33 \u2153 RPM, Purple on 2008 in [[United States|US]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Avenged-Sevenfold-Sounding-The-Seventh-Trumpet/release/2604040|title=Sounding the Seventh Trumpet LP|publisher=Discogs.com|accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' was recorded in November 2000, with a budget of $2,000. When the band members got into the studio, The Rev recorded all the drums in one take, and the other members of the band added their parts to what he had laid down. Zacky Vengeance played lead guitar originally. Then, when Synyster Gates joined the band in early 2001, they recorded a heavy metal version of \"To End the Rapture\" with Gates playing lead guitar. This heavy metal version was first seen on the \"[[Warmness on the Soul]]\" single, and was later featured on the re-release of ''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet''. This is the only album to feature bassist Justin Sane, whom is also credited as playing piano on the original releases. He was briefly replaced by Dameon Ash as a touring bassist after the touring cycle, whom was then replaced by [[Johnny Christ]].\n\n==Release==\nThe release date of this album is theorized in many sources. On the band's official website, it's given as January 31, 2001. However, on archived versions of the website, news updates explain that the album, distributed by Lumberjack Distributions, was originally planned for a late April 2001 release. Due to unknown reasons, it had to be pushed back multiple times, at first for a June 10, then for a June 20 release. A [[Loudwire]] article about the album's 17th anniversary gives July 24 as the actual release date.<ref name=\"Loudwire\">{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/avenged-sevenfold-sounding-the-seventh-trumpet-album-anniversary/ |title=17 Years Ago: Avenged Sevenfold Introduce Themselves With \u2018Sounding the Seventh Trumpet\u2019 |publisher=Loudwire.com |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2018-11-27 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n|rev2 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref>''[[Kerrang!]]'' issue 880 (November 24, 2001).</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Ultimate Guitar]]''\n|rev3score=8.5/10<ref>{{cite web |title=Avenged Sevenfold: Sounding The Seventh Trumpet {{!}} Reviews @ Ultimate-Guitar.com |url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/reviews/compact_discs/avenged_sevenfold/sounding_the_seventh_trumpet/ |website=[[Ultimate Guitar]] |accessdate=3 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n}}\n''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' was generally well received by critics. [[Allmusic]] rated the album three stars out of five and wrote: \"''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' is a magnificent album that is suitable for any fan of [[heavy metal music|metal music]], as Avenged Sevenfold has a firm grasp on all that is extreme.\" The review also praised the tracks \"Darkness Surrounding\" and \"We Come out at Night\" as being \"...excellent [[metalcore]] masterpieces, as the vocal harmonies add to these cuts to evolve the songs into fully atmospheric sonic blasts.\"\n\n==Videography==\nAvenged Sevenfold later released the ''Warmness on the Soul'', which featured a video for the single \"Warmness on the Soul\". The video depicted the band wandering through city streets as M. Shadows' wife, Valary, searched for them. There is a [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] version of \"To End the Rapture\" which was released on the reissue of ''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'' after it was bought by Hopeless Records.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xfi09_avenged-sevenfold-warmness-on-the-s_news |title=Avenged Sevenfold - Warmness On The Soul - Vid\u00e9o Dailymotion |publisher=Dailymotion.com |date=2006-09-25 |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = Avenged Sevenfold, except where noted\n| title1          = To End the Rapture\n| length1         = 1:24\n| title2          = Turn the Other Way\n| length2         = 5:40\n| title3          = [[Darkness Surrounding]]\n| length3         = 4:53\n| title4          = The Art of Subconscious Illusion\n| note4           = featuring Valary DiBenedetto\n| length4         = 3:45\n| title5          = We Come Out at Night\n| length5         = 4:46\n| title6          = Lips of Deceit\n| length6         = 4:09\n| title7          = [[Warmness on the Soul]]\n| length7         = 4:19\n| title8          = An Epic of Time Wasted\n| length8         = 4:18\n| title9          = Breaking Their Hold\n| length9         = 1:11\n| title10         = Forgotten Faces\n| length10        = 3:26\n| title11         = Thick and Thin\n| length11        = 4:15\n| title12         = Streets\n| note12          = written by M. Shadows & Successful Failure\n| length12        = 3:06\n| title13         = Shattered by Broken Dreams\n| length13        = 7:12\n| total_length    = 53:11\n| title_width     = 740px\n}}\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The \"Heavy Metal Version\" of \"To End the Rapture\" was featured on the re-release of ''Sounding the Seventh Trumpet'', replacing the original.\n\n==Personnel==\n;Avenged Sevenfold\n* [[M. Shadows]] \u2013 vocals, acoustic guitar, keyboards\n* [[Zacky Vengeance]] 